# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hardware-abstraction
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hardware-abstraction/abstraction-layer] In computing, an **abstraction layer** or **abstraction level** is a way of hiding the working details of a subsystem.
[src:hardware-abstraction/abstraction-layer] Examples of software models that use layers of abstraction include the OSI model for network protocols, OpenGL, and other graphics libraries, which allow the separation of concerns to facilitate interoperability and platform independence.
[src:hardware-abstraction/abstraction-layer] In computer science, an abstraction layer is a generalization of a conceptual model or algorithm, away from any specific implementation.
[src:hardware-abstraction/abstraction-layer] These generalizations arise from broad similarities that are best encapsulated by models that express similarities present in various specific implementations.
[src:hardware-abstraction/abstraction-layer] The simplification provided by a good abstraction layer allows for easy reuse by distilling a useful concept or design pattern so that situations, where it may be accurately applied, can be quickly recognized.
[src:hardware-abstraction/abstraction-layer] Just composing lower-level elements into a construct doesn't count as an abstraction layer unless it shields users from its underlying complexity.
[src:hardware-abstraction/abstraction-layer] A layer is considered to be on top of another if it depends on it.
[src:hardware-abstraction/abstraction-layer] Every layer can exist without the layers above it, and requires the layers below it to function.
[src:hardware-abstraction/abstraction-layer] Frequently, abstraction layers can be composed into a hierarchy of abstraction levels.
[src:hardware-abstraction/abstraction-layer] The OSI model comprises seven abstraction layers.
[src:hardware-abstraction/abstraction-layer] Each layer of the model encapsulates and addresses a different part of the needs of digital communications, thereby reducing the complexity of the associated engineering solutions.
[src:hardware-abstraction/abstraction-layer] A famous aphorism of David Wheeler is, "All problems in computer science can be solved by another level of indirection." This is often deliberately misquoted with "abstraction" substituted for "indirection." It is also sometimes misattributed to Butler Lampson.
[src:hardware-abstraction/abstraction-layer] Programmable logic is often considered part of the hardware, while the logical definitions are also sometimes seen as part of a device's software or firmware.
[src:hardware-abstraction/abstraction-layer] Firmware may include only low-level software, but can also include all software, including an operating system and applications.
[src:hardware-abstraction/abstraction-layer] The software layers can be further divided into hardware abstraction layers, physical and logical device drivers, repositories such as filesystems, operating system kernels, middleware, applications, and others.
[src:hardware-abstraction/abstraction-layer] A distinction can also be made between low-level programming languages like VHDL, machine language, assembly language and a compiled language, interpreter, or script language.
[src:hardware-abstraction/abstraction-layer] In the Unix operating system, most types of input and output operations are considered to be streams of bytes read from a device or written to a device.
[src:hardware-abstraction/abstraction-layer] This stream of bytes model is used for file I/O, socket I/O, and terminal I/O in order to provide device independence.
[src:hardware-abstraction/abstraction-layer] In order to read and write to a device at the application level, the program calls a function to open the device, which may be a real device, such as a terminal or a virtual device, such as a network port or a file in a file system.
[src:hardware-abstraction/abstraction-layer] The device's physical characteristics are mediated by the operating system, which in turn presents an abstract interface that allows the programmer to read and write bytes from/to the device.
[src:hardware-abstraction/abstraction-layer] The operating system then performs the actual transformation needed to read and write the stream of bytes to the device.
[src:hardware-abstraction/abstraction-layer] Most graphics libraries, such as OpenGL, provide an abstract graphical device model as an interface.
[src:hardware-abstraction/abstraction-layer] The library is responsible for translating the commands provided by the programmer into the specific device commands needed to draw the graphical elements and objects.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] Internally, ACPI advertises the available components and their functions to the operating system kernel using instruction lists ("methods") provided through the system firmware (UEFI or BIOS), which the kernel parses.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] ACPI then executes the desired operations written in *ACPI Machine Language* (such as the initialization of hardware components) using an embedded minimal virtual machine.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] Intel, Microsoft and Toshiba originally developed the standard, while HP, Huawei and Phoenix also participated later.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] In October 2013, ACPI Special Interest Group (ACPI SIG), the original developers of the ACPI standard, agreed to transfer all assets to the UEFI Forum, in which all future development will take place.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] The latest version of the standard 6.6 was released in 13 May 2025.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] The firmware-level ACPI has three main components: the ACPI tables, the ACPI BIOS, and the ACPI registers.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] The ACPI BIOS generates ACPI tables and loads ACPI tables into main memory.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] Much of the firmware ACPI functionality is provided in bytecode of *ACPI Machine Language* (*AML*), a Turing-complete, domain-specific low-level language, stored in the ACPI tables.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] To make use of the ACPI tables, the operating system must have an interpreter for the AML bytecode.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] A reference AML interpreter implementation is provided by the *ACPI Component Architecture* (*ACPICA*).
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] At the BIOS development time, AML bytecode is compiled from *ACPI Source Language* (*ASL*) code.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] The **ACPI Component Architecture** (**ACPICA**), mainly written by Intel's engineers, provides an open-source platform-independent reference implementation of the operating system–related ACPI code.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] The ACPICA code is used by Linux, Haiku, ArcaOS and FreeBSD, which supplement it with their operating-system specific code.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] The first revision of the ACPI specification was released in December 1996, supporting 16, 24 and 32-bit addressing spaces.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] It was not until August 2000 that ACPI received 64-bit address support as well as support for multiprocessor workstations and servers with revision 2.0.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] In 1999, then Microsoft CEO Bill Gates stated in an e-mail that Linux would benefit from ACPI without them having to do work and suggested to make it Windows-only.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] Released in June 2009, revision 4.0 of the ACPI specification added various new features to the design; most notable are the USB 3.0 support, logical processor idling support, and x2APIC support.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] Initially ACPI was exclusive to x86 architecture; Revision 5.0 of the ACPI specification was released in December 2011, which added the ARM architecture support.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] The revision 5.1 was released in July 2014.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] The latest revision 6.6, which was released in May 2025, added the RISC-V support.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] Microsoft's Windows 98 was the first operating system to implement ACPI, but its implementation was somewhat buggy or incomplete, although some of the problems associated with it were caused by the first-generation ACPI hardware.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] Other operating systems, including later versions of Windows, macOS (x86 macOS only), eComStation, ArcaOS, FreeBSD (since FreeBSD 5.0), NetBSD (since NetBSD 1.6), OpenBSD (since OpenBSD 3.8), HP-UX, OpenVMS, Linux, GNU/Hurd and PC versions of Solaris, have at least some support for ACPI.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] Some newer operating systems, like Windows Vista, require the computer to have an ACPI-compliant BIOS, and since Windows 8, the S0ix/Modern Standby state was implemented.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] Windows operating systems use acpi.sys to access ACPI events.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] The 2.4 series of the Linux kernel had only minimal support for ACPI, with better support implemented (and enabled by default) from kernel version 2.6.0 onwards.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] Old ACPI BIOS implementations tend to be quite buggy, and consequently are not supported by later operating systems.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] For example, Windows 2000, Windows XP, and Windows Server 2003 only use ACPI if the BIOS date is after January 1, 1999.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] Similarly, Linux kernel 2.6 may not use ACPI if the BIOS date is before January 1, 2001.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] Linux-based operating systems can provide handling of ACPI events via acpid.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] Once an OSPM-compatible operating system activates ACPI, it takes exclusive control of all aspects of power management and device configuration.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] The OSPM implementation must expose an ACPI-compatible environment to device drivers, which exposes certain system, device and processor states.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] The specification also defines a *Legacy* state: the state of an operating system which does not support ACPI.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] In this state, the hardware and power are not managed via ACPI, effectively disabling ACPI.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] For describing the idle states of groupings of components (e.g. a package containing several cores), the _LPI (low power idle) method is used.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] This should not be confused with Intel's private LPIT table, used to describe S0ix sleep in package C10 or PCH SLP_S0 state.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] While a device or processor operates (D0 and C0, respectively), it can be in one of several power-performance states.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] These states are implementation-dependent.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] P0 is always the highest-performance state, with P1 to P*n* being successively lower-performance states.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] The total number of states is device or processor dependent, but can be no greater than 16.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] P-states have become known as SpeedStep in Intel processors, as PowerNow! or Cool'n'Quiet in AMD processors, and as PowerSaver in VIA processors.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] See Dynamic frequency scaling § Autonomous frequency scaling for a brief description of a newer control method based on the ACPI Collaborative Processor Performance Control (CPPC).
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] This new method allows hundreds of possible states, and for the processor to autonomously to choose from a given range of states.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] ACPI-compliant systems interact with hardware through either a "Function Fixed Hardware (FFH) Interface", or a platform-independent hardware programming model which relies on platform-specific ACPI Machine Language (AML) provided by the original equipment manufacturer (OEM).
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] Function Fixed Hardware interfaces are platform-specific features, provided by platform manufacturers for the purposes of performance and failure recovery.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] Standard Intel-based PCs have a fixed function interface defined by Intel, which provides a set of core functionality that reduces an ACPI-compliant system's need for full driver stacks for providing basic functionality during boot time or in the case of major system failure.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] ACPI Platform Error Interface (APEI) is a specification for reporting of hardware errors, e.g. chipset, RAM to the operating system.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] ACPI defines many tables that provide the interface between an ACPI-compliant operating system and system firmware (BIOS or UEFI).
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] This includes RSDP, RSDT, XSDT, FADT, FACS, DSDT, SSDT, MADT, and MCFG, for example.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] The tables allow description of system hardware in a platform-independent manner, and are presented as either fixed-formatted data structures or in AML.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] The main AML table is the DSDT (differentiated system description table).
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] The AML can be decompiled by tools like Intel's iASL (open-source, part of ACPICA) for purposes like patching the tables for expanding OS compatibility.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] The Root System Description Pointer (RSDP) is located in a platform-dependent manner, and describes the rest of the tables.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] A custom ACPI table called the Windows Platform Binary Table (WPBT) is used by Microsoft to allow vendors to add software into the Windows OS automatically.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] Lenovo have been caught using this feature to install harmful software such as Superfish.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] Also, Gigabyte Technology have been found using this feature to install its OEM software.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] Samsung shipped PCs with Windows Update disabled.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] Windows versions older than Windows 7 do not support this feature, but alternative techniques can be used.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] This behavior has been compared to rootkits.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] Ubuntu founder Mark Shuttleworth says ACPI is a security risk.
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] He says "arguing for ACPI on your next-generation device is arguing for a trojan horse of monumental proportions to be installed in your living room and in your data centre" and "firmware on your device is the NSA's best friend".
[src:hardware-abstraction/acpi] In November 2003, Linus Torvalds—author of the Linux kernel—described ACPI as "a complete design disaster in every way".
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] At its core, the operating system is known as the **Android Open Source Project** (**AOSP**) and is free and open-source software (FOSS) primarily licensed under the Apache License.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Other Google services including Firebase Cloud Messaging, used for push notifications, are recommended for applications.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] While AOSP is free, the "Android" name and logo are trademarks of Google, who restrict the use of Android branding on "uncertified" products.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] The majority of smartphones based on AOSP run Google's ecosystem—which is known simply as Android—some with vendor-customized user interfaces and software suites, for example One UI.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Commercial products like micro consoles and virtual reality headset have also used Android.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Since 2011 Android has been the most used operating system worldwide on smartphones.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] It has the largest installed base of any operating system in the world with over three billion monthly active users and accounting for 46% of the global operating system market.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] In 2005, Rubin tried to negotiate deals with Samsung and HTC.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Shortly afterwards, Google acquired the company in July of that year for at least $50 million; this was Google's "best deal ever" according to Google's then-vice president of corporate development, David Lawee, in 2010.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Android's key employees, including Rubin, Miner, Sears, and White, joined Google as part of the acquisition.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Not much was known about the secretive Android Inc. at the time, with the company having provided few details other than that it was making software for mobile phones.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] At Google, the team led by Rubin developed a mobile device platform powered by the Linux kernel.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Google marketed the platform to handset makers and carriers on the promise of providing a flexible, upgradeable system.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Google had "lined up a series of hardware components and software partners and signaled to carriers that it was open to various degrees of cooperation".
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Speculation about Google's intention to enter the mobile communications market continued to build through December 2006.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] An early prototype had a close resemblance to a BlackBerry phone, with no touchscreen and a physical QWERTY keyboard, but the arrival of Apple's 2007 iPhone meant that Android "had to go back to the drawing board".
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Google later changed its Android specification documents to state that "Touchscreens will be supported", although "the Product was designed with the presence of discrete physical buttons as an assumption, therefore a touchscreen cannot completely replace physical buttons".
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] By 2008, both Nokia and BlackBerry announced touch-based smartphones to rival the iPhone 3G, and Android's focus eventually switched to just touchscreens.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] The first commercially available smartphone running Android was the HTC Dream, also known as T-Mobile G1, announced on September 23, 2008.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Within a year, the Open Handset Alliance faced two other open source competitors, the Symbian Foundation and the LiMo Foundation, the latter also developing a Linux-based mobile operating system like Google.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] In September 2007, Google had filed several patent applications in the area of mobile telephony.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] On September 23, 2008, Android was introduced by Andy Rubin, Larry Page, Sergey Brin, Cole Brodman, Christopher Schlaeffer and Peter Chou at a press conference in a New York City subway station.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Since 2008, Android has seen numerous updates which have incrementally improved the operating system, adding new features and fixing bugs in previous releases.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] In 2010, Google launched its Nexus series of devices, a lineup in which Google partnered with different device manufacturers to produce new devices and introduce new Android versions.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] The series was described as having "played a pivotal role in Android's history by introducing new software iterations and hardware standards across the board", and became known for its "bloat-free" software with "timely ... updates".
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] At its developer conference in May 2013, Google announced a special version of the Samsung Galaxy S4, where, instead of using Samsung's own Android customization, the phone ran "stock Android" and was promised to receive new system updates fast.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] The device would become the start of the Google Play edition program, and was followed by other devices, including the HTC One Google Play edition, and Moto G Google Play edition.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] In 2015, *Ars Technica* wrote that "Earlier this week, the last of the Google Play edition Android phones in Google's online storefront were listed as "no longer available for sale" and that "Now they're all gone, and it looks a whole lot like the program has wrapped up".
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] From 2008 to 2013, Hugo Barra served as product spokesperson, representing Android at press conferences and Google I/O, Google's annual developer-focused conference.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] He left Google in August 2013 to join Chinese phone maker Xiaomi.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Less than six months earlier, Google's then-CEO Larry Page announced in a blog post that Andy Rubin had moved from the Android division to take on new projects at Google, and that Sundar Pichai would become the new Android lead.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Pichai himself would eventually switch positions, becoming the new CEO of Google in August 2015 following the company's restructure into the Alphabet conglomerate, making Hiroshi Lockheimer the new head of Android.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] On Android 4.4, *KitKat*, shared writing access to MicroSD memory cards has been locked for user-installed applications, to which only the dedicated directories with respective package names, located inside `Android/data/`, remained writeable.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Writing access has been reinstated with Android 5 *Lollipop* through the backwards-incompatible *Google Storage Access Framework* interface.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] In June 2014, Google announced Android One, a set of "hardware reference models" that would "allow [device makers] to easily create high-quality phones at low costs", designed for consumers in developing countries.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] In September, Google announced the first set of Android One phones for release in India.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] However, *Recode* reported in June 2015 that the project was "a disappointment", citing "reluctant consumers and manufacturing partners" and "misfires from the search company that has never quite cracked hardware".
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Plans to relaunch Android One surfaced in August 2015, with Africa announced as the next location for the program a week later.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] A report from *The Information* in January 2017 stated that Google is expanding its low-cost Android One program into the United States, although *The Verge* notes that the company will presumably not produce the actual devices itself.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Google introduced the Pixel and Pixel XL smartphones in October 2016, marketed as being the first phones made by Google, and exclusively featured certain software features, such as the Google Assistant, before wider rollout.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] The Pixel phones replaced the Nexus series, with a new generation of Pixel phones launched in October 2017.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] In May 2019, the operating system became entangled in the trade war between China and the United States involving Huawei, which, like many other tech firms, had become dependent on access to the Android platform.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] In the summer of 2019, Huawei announced it would create an alternative operating system to Android known as Harmony OS, and has filed for intellectual property rights across major global markets.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Under such sanctions Huawei has long-term plans to replace Android in 2022 with the new operating system, as Harmony OS was originally designed for internet of things devices, rather than for smartphones and tablets.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] On August 22, 2019, it was announced that Android "Q" would officially be branded as Android 10, ending the historic practice of naming major versions after desserts.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Google stated that these names were not "inclusive" to international users (due either to the aforementioned foods not being internationally known, or being difficult to pronounce in some languages).
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] On the same day, *Android Police* reported that Google had commissioned a statue of a giant number "10" to be installed in the lobby of the developers' new office.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Android 10 was released on September 3, 2019, to Google Pixel phones first.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] In late 2021, some users reported that they were unable to dial emergency services.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] The problem was caused by a combination of bugs in Android and in the Microsoft Teams app; both companies released updates addressing the issue.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] On December 12, 2024, Google announced Android XR.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] It is a new operating system developed by Google, designed for virtual reality and augmented reality devices, such as VR headsets and smart glasses.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] It was built in collaboration with Samsung and Qualcomm.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] The platform is also focused on supporting developers with tools like ARCore and Unity to build applications for upcoming XR devices.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] In March 2025, Google announced its plans to consolidate Android development to internal sources.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] While public developers will no longer be able to contribute, the Android source will still be published.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Android's default user interface is mainly based on direct manipulation, using touch inputs that loosely correspond to real-world actions, like swiping, tapping, pinching, and reverse pinching to manipulate on-screen objects, along with a virtual keyboard.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Game controllers and full-size physical keyboards are supported via Bluetooth or USB.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] The response to user input is designed to be immediate and provides a fluid touch interface, often using the vibration capabilities of the device to provide haptic feedback to the user.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Android devices boot to the home screen, the primary navigation and information "hub" on Android devices, analogous to the desktop found on personal computers.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Android home screens are typically made up of app icons and widgets; app icons launch the associated app, whereas widgets display live, auto-updating content, such as a weather forecast, the user's email inbox, or a news ticker directly on the home screen.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] A home screen may be made up of several pages, between which the user can swipe back and forth.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Third-party apps available on Google Play and other app stores can extensively re-theme the home screen, and even mimic the look of other operating systems, such as Windows Phone.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Most manufacturers customize the look and features of their Android devices to differentiate themselves from their competitors.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Along the top of the screen is a status bar, showing information about the device and its connectivity.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] This status bar can be pulled (swiped) down to reveal a notification screen where apps display important information or updates, as well as quick access to system controls and toggles such as display brightness, connectivity settings (WiFi, Bluetooth, cellular data), audio mode, and flashlight.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Vendors may implement extended settings such as the ability to adjust the flashlight brightness.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Notifications are "short, timely, and relevant information about your app when it's not in use", and when tapped, users are directed to a screen inside the app relating to the notification.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Beginning with Android 4.1 "Jelly Bean", "expandable notifications" allow the user to tap an icon on the notification in order for it to expand and display more information and possible app actions right from the notification.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] An "All Apps" screen lists all installed applications, with the ability for users to drag an app from the list onto the home screen.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] The app list may be accessed using a gesture or a button, depending on the Android version.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] A "Recents" screen, also known as "Overview", lets users switch between recently used apps.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] The recent list may appear side-by-side or overlapping, depending on the Android version and manufacturer.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Many early Android OS smartphones were equipped with a dedicated search button for quick access to a web search engine and individual apps' internal search feature.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] More recent devices typically allow the former through a long press or swipe away from the home button.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] The dedicated option key, also known as menu key, and its on-screen simulation, is no longer supported since Android version 10.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Google recommends mobile application developers to locate menus within the user interface.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] On more recent phones, its place is occupied by a task key used to access the list of recently used apps when actuated.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Depending on device, its long press may simulate a menu button press or engage split screen view, the latter of which is the default behaviour since stock Android version 7.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Native support for split screen view has been added in stock Android version 7.0 *Nougat*.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] The earliest vendor-customized Android-based smartphones known to have featured a split-screen view mode are the 2012 Samsung Galaxy S3 and Note 2, the former of which received this feature with the *premium suite* upgrade delivered in TouchWiz with Android 4.1 Jelly Bean.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Android has supported a rudimentary Desktop Mode in developer options.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] A native desktop mode was rolled out in March 2026 to Pixel devices from the Pixel 8 onward; tablets received it with Android 16 QPR3, with the intention to roll this feature out to more devices in the future.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Most Android devices come with preinstalled Google apps including Gmail, Google Maps, Google Chrome, YouTube, Google TV, and others.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Java is still supported (originally the only option for user-space programs, and is often mixed with Kotlin), as is C++.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Java or other JVM languages, such as Kotlin, may be combined with C/C++, together with a choice of non-default runtimes that allow better C++ support.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] The SDK includes a comprehensive set of development tools, including a debugger, software libraries, a handset emulator based on QEMU, documentation, sample code, and tutorials.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Initially, Google's supported integrated development environment (IDE) was Eclipse using the Android Development Tools (ADT) plugin; in December 2014, Google released Android Studio, based on IntelliJ IDEA, as its primary IDE for Android application development.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Other development tools are available, including a native development kit (NDK) for applications or extensions in C or C++, Google App Inventor, a visual environment for novice programmers, and various cross platform mobile web applications frameworks.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] In January 2014, Google unveiled a framework based on Apache Cordova for porting Chrome HTML 5 web applications to Android, wrapped in a native application shell.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Additionally, Firebase was acquired by Google in 2014 that provides helpful tools for app and web developers.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Google Play Store is the primary application store installed on Android devices that comply with Google's compatibility requirements and license the Google Mobile Services software.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Google Play Store allows users to browse, download and update applications published by Google and third-party developers; as of January 2021, there are more than three million applications available for Android in Play Store.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] As of July 2013, 50 billion application installations had been performed.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Some carriers offer direct carrier billing for Google Play application purchases, where the cost of the application is added to the user's monthly bill.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] As of May 2017, there are over one billion active users a month for Gmail, Android, Chrome, Google Play and Maps.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Examples of these third-party stores have included the Amazon Appstore, GetJar, and SlideMe.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] F-Droid, another alternative marketplace, seeks to only provide applications that are distributed under free and open source licenses.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] In October 2020, Google removed several Android applications from Play Store, as they were identified breaching its data collection rules.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] The firm was informed by International Digital Accountability Council (IDAC) that apps for children like *Number Coloring*, *Princess Salon* and *Cats & Cosplay*, with collective downloads of 20 million, were violating Google's policies.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] At the Windows 11 announcement event in June 2021, Microsoft showcased the new Windows Subsystem for Android (WSA) to enable support for the Android Open Source Project (AOSP), but it has since been deprecated.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] It was intended to allow users to run Android apps and games on their Windows 11 desktop.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Microsoft ended WSA support on March 5, 2025.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] The storage of Android devices can be expanded using secondary devices such as SD cards.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Android recognizes two types of secondary storage: *portable* storage (which is used by default), and *adoptable* storage.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Portable storage is treated as an external storage device.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Adoptable storage, introduced on Android 6.0, allows the internal storage of the device to be spanned with the SD card, treating it as an extension of the internal storage.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] This has the disadvantage of preventing the memory card from being used with another device unless it is reformatted.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Android 4.4 introduced the Storage Access Framework (SAF), a set of APIs for accessing files on the device's filesystem.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] As of Android 11, Android has required apps to conform to a data privacy policy known as *scoped storage*, under which apps may only automatically have access to certain directories (such as those for pictures, music, and video), and app-specific directories they have created themselves.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Apps are required to use the SAF to access any other part of the filesystem.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Since Android devices are usually battery-powered, Android is designed to manage processes to keep power consumption at a minimum.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] When an application is not in use the system suspends its operation so that, while available for immediate use rather than closed, it does not use battery power or CPU resources.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Android manages the applications stored in memory automatically: when memory is low, the system will begin invisibly and automatically closing inactive processes, starting with those that have been inactive for the longest amount of time.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Lifehacker reported in 2011 that third-party task-killer applications were doing more harm than good.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] "App's Not Responding"), prevent a Bluetooth audio client from controlling the system volume ("Disable absolute volume"), and adjust the duration of transition animations or deactivate them completely to speed up navigation.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Developer options are initially hidden since Android 4.2 "Jelly Bean", but can be enabled by actuating the operating system's build number in the device information seven times.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Hiding developers options again requires deleting user data for the "Settings" app, possibly resetting some other preferences, or in recent Android versions, turning off the Developer options master switch.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] The main hardware platform for Android is 64-bit ARM (i.e. the ARMv8-A architecture) and the 32-bit ARMv7-A architecture, with x86-64 and the 32-bit x86 architectures also being officially supported in later versions of Android.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] The unofficial Android-x86 project provided support for x86 architectures ahead of the official support.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Since 2012, Android devices with Intel processors began to appear, including phones and tablets.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] While gaining support for 64-bit platforms, Android was first made to run on 64-bit x86 and then on ARM64.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] An unofficial experimental port of the operating system to 64-bit RISC-V architecture was released in 2021.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Requirements for the minimum amount of RAM for smartphones running Android 15 range from 4 GB of RAM for full Android to 2 GB, in which case the smartphone manufacturers must use the Android Go Edition.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Android supports all versions of OpenGL ES and Vulkan (and version 1.1 available for some devices).
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Android devices incorporate many optional hardware components, including still or video cameras, GPS, orientation sensors, dedicated gaming controls, accelerometers, gyroscopes, barometers, magnetometers, proximity sensors, pressure sensors, thermometers, and touchscreens.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Some hardware components are not required, but became standard in certain classes of devices, such as smartphones, and additional requirements apply if they are present.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Some other hardware was initially required, but those requirements have been relaxed or eliminated altogether.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] For example, as Android was developed initially as a phone OS, hardware such as microphones were required, while over time the phone function became optional.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Android used to require an autofocus camera, which was relaxed to a fixed-focus camera if present at all, since the camera was dropped as a requirement entirely when Android started to be used on set-top boxes.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] In addition to running on smartphones and tablets, several vendors run Android natively on regular PC hardware with a keyboard and mouse.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] In addition to their availability on commercially available hardware, similar PC hardware-friendly versions of Android are freely available from the Android-x86 project, including customized Android 4.4.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Using the Android emulator that is part of the Android SDK, or third-party emulators, Android can also run non-natively on x86 architectures.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Chinese companies are building a PC and mobile operating system, based on Android, to "compete directly with Microsoft Windows and Google Android".
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] The Chinese Academy of Engineering noted that "more than a dozen" companies were customizing Android following a Chinese ban on the use of Windows 8 on government PCs.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Android runs on a wide variety of devices such as smartphones, tablets, cars, computers, smart watches, and smart TVs.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] However, the vast majority of Android-powered devices are smartphones.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] Unlike its two main competitors in the mobile operating system space, namely iOS and HarmonyOS, Android devices are made by many different original equipment manufacturers.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p01] These OEMs include Samsung, Xiaomi, Vivo, Oppo, iQOO, OnePlus, Honor, Google, Sony, Lenovo, Sharp, Realme, Nothing, and Tecno.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Android is developed by Google until the latest changes and updates are ready to be released, at which point the source code is made available to the Android Open Source Project (AOSP), an open source initiative led by Google.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] The first source code release happened as part of the initial release in 2007.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] All releases are under the Apache License.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] The AOSP code can be found with minimal modifications on select devices, mainly the former Nexus and current Android One series of devices.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] However, most original equipment manufacturers (OEMs) customize the source code to run on their hardware.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Android's source code does not contain the device drivers, often proprietary, that are needed for certain hardware components, and does not contain the source code of Google Play Services, which many apps depend on.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] As a result, most Android devices, including Google's own, ship with a combination of free and open source and proprietary software, with the software required for accessing Google services falling into the latter category.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] In response to this, there are some projects that build complete operating systems based on AOSP as free software, the first being CyanogenMod (see section Open-source community below).
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Google provides annual Android releases, both for factory installation in new devices, and for over-the-air updates to existing devices.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] The extensive variation of hardware in Android devices has caused significant delays for software upgrades and security patches.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Each upgrade has had to be specifically tailored, a time- and resource-consuming process.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Except for devices within the Google Nexus and Pixel brands, updates have often arrived months after the release of the new version, or not at all.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Manufacturers often prioritize their newest devices and leave old ones behind.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Additional delays can be introduced by wireless carriers who, after receiving updates from manufacturers, further customize Android to their needs and conduct extensive testing on their networks before sending out the upgrade.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] There are also situations in which upgrades are impossible due to a manufacturer not updating necessary drivers.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] The lack of after-sale support from manufacturers and carriers has been widely criticized by consumer groups and the technology media.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Some commentators have noted that the industry has a financial incentive not to upgrade their devices, as the lack of updates for existing devices fuels the purchase of newer ones, an attitude described as "insulting".
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] *The Guardian* complained that the method of distribution for updates is complicated only because manufacturers and carriers have designed it that way.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] In 2011, Google partnered with a number of industry players to announce an "Android Update Alliance", pledging to deliver timely updates for every device for 18 months after its release; however, there has not been another official word about that alliance since its announcement.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] In 2012, Google began de-coupling certain aspects of the operating system (particularly its central applications) so they could be updated through the Google Play store independently of the OS.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] One of those components, Google Play Services, is a closed-source system-level process providing APIs for Google services, installed automatically on nearly all devices running Android 2.2 "Froyo" and higher.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] With these changes, Google can add new system functions and update apps without having to distribute an upgrade to the operating system itself.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] As a result, Android 4.2 and 4.3 "Jelly Bean" contained relatively fewer user-facing changes, focusing more on minor changes and platform improvements.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] HTC's then-executive Jason Mackenzie called monthly security updates "unrealistic" in 2015, and Google was trying to persuade carriers to exclude security patches from the full testing procedures.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] As stated by *Bloomberg*: "As smartphones get more capable, complex and hackable, having the latest software work closely with the hardware is increasingly important".
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Hiroshi Lockheimer, the Android lead, admitted that "It's not an ideal situation", further commenting that the lack of updates is "the weakest link on security on Android".
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Wireless carriers were described in the report as the "most challenging discussions", due to their slow approval time while testing on their networks, despite some carriers, including Verizon Wireless and Sprint Corporation, already shortening their approval times.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] In a further effort for persuasion, Google shared a list of top phone makers measured by updated devices with its Android partners, and is considering making the list public.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Mike Chan, co-founder of phone maker Nextbit and former Android developer, said that "The best way to solve this problem is a massive re-architecture of the operating system", "or Google could invest in training manufacturers and carriers 'to be good Android citizens'".
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] In May 2017, with the announcement of Android 8.0, Google introduced Project Treble, a major re-architect of the Android OS framework designed to make it easier, faster, and less costly for manufacturers to update devices to newer versions of Android.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Project Treble separates the vendor implementation (device-specific, lower-level software written by silicon manufacturers) from the Android OS framework via a new "vendor interface".
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] In Android 7.0 and earlier, no formal vendor interface exists, so device makers must update large portions of the Android code to move a device to a newer version of the operating system.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] In May 2019, with the announcement of Android 10, Google introduced Project Mainline to simplify and expedite delivery of updates to the Android ecosystem.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Project Mainline enables updates to core OS components through the Google Play Store.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] As a result, important security and performance improvements that previously needed to be part of full OS updates can be downloaded and installed as easily as an app update.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Google reported rolling out new amendments in Android 12 aimed at making the use of third-party application stores easier.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] This announcement rectified the concerns reported regarding the development of Android apps, including a fight over an alternative in-app payment system and difficulties faced by businesses moving online because of COVID-19.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Android's kernel is based on the Linux kernel's long-term support (LTS) branches.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] The actual kernel depends on the individual device.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Android's variant of the Linux kernel has further architectural changes that are implemented by Google outside the typical Linux kernel development cycle, such as the inclusion of components like device trees, ashmem, ION, and different out of memory (OOM) handling.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Certain features that Google contributed back to the Linux kernel, notably a power management feature called "wakelocks", were initially rejected by mainline kernel developers partly because they felt that Google did not show any intent to maintain its own code.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Google engineer Patrick Brady once stated in the company's developer conference that "Android is not Linux", with *Computerworld* adding that "Let me make it simple for you, without Linux, there is no Android".
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] *Ars Technica* wrote that "Although Android is built on top of the Linux kernel, the platform has very little in common with the conventional desktop Linux stack".
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] In August 2011, Linus Torvalds said that "eventually Android and Linux would come back to a common kernel, but it will probably not be for four to five years".
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] In December 2011, Greg Kroah-Hartman announced the start of Android Mainlining Project, which aims to put some Android drivers, patches and features back into the Linux kernel, starting in Linux 3.3.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Linux included the autosleep and wakelocks capabilities in the 3.5 kernel, after many previous attempts at a merger.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] The interfaces are the same but the upstream Linux implementation allows for two different suspend modes: to memory (the traditional suspend that Android uses), and to disk (hibernate, as it is known on the desktop).
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Google maintains a public code repository that contains their experimental work to re-base Android off the latest stable Linux versions.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Android is a Linux distribution according to the Linux Foundation, Google's open-source chief Chris DiBona, and several journalists.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Others, such as Google engineer Patrick Brady, say that Android is not Linux in the traditional Unix-like Linux distribution sense; Android does not include the GNU C Library (it uses Bionic as an alternative C library) and some other components typically found in Linux distributions.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] With the release of Android Oreo in 2017, Google began to require that devices shipped with new SoCs had Linux kernel version 4.4 or newer, for security reasons.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Existing devices upgraded to Oreo, and new products launched with older SoCs, were exempt from this rule.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] The flash storage on Android devices is split into several partitions, such as `/system/` for the operating system itself, and `/data/` for user data and application installations.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] In contrast to typical desktop Linux distributions, Android device owners are not given root access to the operating system and sensitive partitions such as `/system/` are partially read-only.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] However, root access can be obtained by exploiting security flaws in Android, which is used frequently by the open-source community to enhance the capabilities and customizability of their devices, but also by malicious parties to install viruses and malware.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] The unlocking process resets the system to factory state, erasing all user data.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Proprietary frameworks like Samsung Knox limit or block attempts at rooting.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Google's Play Integrity API allows developers to check for any signs of tampering, although the fairness of the tests have been criticized.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] On top of the Linux kernel, there are the middleware, libraries and APIs written in C, and application software running on an application framework which includes Java-compatible libraries.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Development of the Linux kernel continues independently of Android's other source code projects.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Android uses Android Runtime (ART) as its runtime environment (introduced in version 4.4), which uses ahead-of-time (AOT) compilation to entirely compile the application bytecode into machine code upon the installation of an application.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] In Android 4.4, ART was an experimental feature and not enabled by default; it became the only runtime option in the next major version of Android, 5.0.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] In versions no longer supported, until version 5.0 when ART took over, Android previously used Dalvik as a process virtual machine with trace-based just-in-time (JIT) compilation to run Dalvik "dex-code" (Dalvik Executable), which is usually translated from the Java bytecode.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Following the trace-based JIT principle, in addition to interpreting the majority of application code, Dalvik performs the compilation and native execution of select frequently executed code segments ("traces") each time an application is launched.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] For its Java library, the Android platform uses a subset of the now discontinued Apache Harmony project.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] In December 2015, Google announced that the next version of Android would switch to a Java implementation based on the OpenJDK project.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Android's standard C library, Bionic, was developed by Google specifically for Android, as a derivation of the BSD's standard C library code.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Bionic itself has been designed with several major features specific to the Linux kernel.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] The main benefits of using Bionic instead of the GNU C Library (glibc) or uClibc are its smaller runtime footprint, and optimization for low-frequency CPUs.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] At the same time, Bionic is licensed under the terms of the BSD licence, which Google finds more suitable for the Android's overall licensing model.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Aiming for a different licensing model, toward the end of 2012, Google switched the Bluetooth stack in Android from the GPL-licensed BlueZ to the Apache-licensed BlueDroid.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] A new Bluetooth stack, called Gabeldorsche, was developed to try to fix the bugs in the BlueDroid implementation.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Android does not have a native X Window System by default, nor does it support the full set of standard GNU libraries.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] This made it difficult to port existing Linux applications or libraries to Android, until version r5 of the Android Native Development Kit brought support for applications written completely in C or C++.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Libraries written in C may also be used in applications by injection of a small shim and usage of the JNI.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] In current versions of Android, "Toybox", a collection of command-line utilities (mostly for use by apps, as Android does not provide a command-line interface by default), is used (since the release of Marshmallow) replacing a similar "Toolbox" collection found in previous Android versions.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Community releases often come pre-rooted and contain modifications not provided by the original vendor, such as the ability to overclock or over/undervolt the device's processor, or security enhancements beyond what is included in the stock OS.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] CyanogenMod was the most widely used community firmware; after its abrupt discontinuation in 2016, a community fork known as LineageOS was established as a spiritual continuation of the project.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Historically, device manufacturers and mobile carriers have typically been unsupportive of third-party firmware development.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Manufacturers express concern about improper functioning of devices running unofficial software and the support costs resulting from this.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Moreover, modified firmware such as CyanogenMod sometimes offer features, such as tethering, for which carriers would otherwise charge a premium.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] As a result, technical obstacles including locked bootloaders and restricted access to root permissions are common in many devices.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] However, despite manufacturer acceptance, some carriers in the US still require that phones are locked down.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Android was also ported by the community to Apple's iPhone, iPad and iPod touch devices as a consequence of porting the Linux kernel on Apple devices.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] In 2010, OpeniBoot and subsequently iDroid were released to allow dual booting iOS and Android 2.3.3 'Gingerbread' on jailbroken iPhone or iPod Touch devices, which was ultimately declared as discontinued in 2012.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] In 2020, David Wang under his company Corellium released Project Sandcastle which made Android run on the iPhone 7.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Internally, Android identifies each supported device by its **device codename**, a short string, which may or may not be similar to the model name used in marketing the device.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] For example, the device codename of the Pixel smartphone is *sailfish*.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] The device codename is usually not visible to the end user, but is important for determining compatibility with modified Android versions.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] It is sometimes also mentioned in articles discussing a device, because it allows to distinguish different hardware variants of a device, even if the manufacturer offers them under the same name.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] The device codename is available to running applications under `android.os.Build.DEVICE`.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] In 2020, Google launched the Android Partner Vulnerability Initiative to improve the security of Android.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] They also formed an Android security team.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Research from security company Trend Micro lists premium service abuse as the most common type of Android malware, where text messages are sent from infected phones to premium-rate telephone numbers without the consent or even knowledge of the user.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Other malware displays unwanted and intrusive advertisements on the device, or sends personal information to unauthorised third parties.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Google maintains that dangerous malware is actually extremely rare, and a survey conducted by F-Secure showed that only 0.5% of Android malware reported had come from the Google Play store.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Analysis of data traffic by popular smartphones running variants of Android found substantial by-default data collection and sharing with no opt-out by this pre-installed software.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Both of these issues are not addressed or cannot be addressed by security patches.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] They were reportedly able to read almost all smartphone information, including SMS, location, emails, and notes.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] GCHQ has, according to *The Guardian*, a wiki-style guide of different apps and advertising networks, and the different data that can be siphoned from each.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Later that week, the Finnish Angry Birds developer Rovio announced that it was reconsidering its relationships with its advertising platforms in the light of these revelations, and called upon the wider industry to do the same.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] The documents revealed a further effort by the intelligence agencies to intercept Google Maps searches and queries submitted from Android and other smartphones to collect location information in bulk.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Leaked documents codenamed Vault 7 and dated from 2013 to 2016, detail the capabilities of the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) to perform electronic surveillance and cyber warfare, including the ability to compromise the operating systems of most smartphones (including Android).
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] In August 2015, Google announced that devices in the Google Nexus series would begin to receive monthly security patches.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Ron Amadeo of *Ars Technica* wrote also in August 2015 that "Android was originally designed, above all else, to be widely adopted.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] As such, security has become a big issue.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Android still uses a software update chain-of-command designed back when the Android ecosystem had zero devices to update, and it just doesn't work".
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Following news of Google's monthly schedule, some manufacturers, including Samsung and LG, promised to issue monthly security updates, but, as noted by Jerry Hildenbrand in *Android Central* in February 2016, "instead we got a few updates on specific versions of a small handful of models.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] They also wrote that "About half of devices in use at the end of 2016 had not received a platform security update in the previous year", stating that their work would continue to focus on streamlining the security updates program for easier deployment by manufacturers.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Furthermore, in a comment to *TechCrunch*, Ludwig stated that the wait time for security updates had been reduced from "six to nine weeks down to just a few days", with 78% of flagship devices in North America being up-to-date on security at the end of 2016.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Patches to bugs found in the core operating system often do not reach users of older and lower-priced devices.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] However, the open-source nature of Android allows security contractors to take existing devices and adapt them for highly secure uses.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] For example, Samsung has worked with General Dynamics through their Open Kernel Labs acquisition to rebuild *Jelly Bean* on top of their hardened microvisor for the "Knox" project.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Android smartphones have the ability to report the location of Wi-Fi access points, encountered as phone users move around, to build databases containing the physical locations of hundreds of millions of such access points.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] These databases form electronic maps to locate smartphones, allowing them to run apps like Foursquare, Google Latitude, Facebook Places, and to deliver location-based ads.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Third party monitoring software such as TaintDroid, an academic research-funded project, can, in some cases, detect when personal information is being sent from applications to remote servers.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] In 2018, Norwegian security firm Promon has unearthed a serious Android security hole which can be exploited to steal login credentials, access messages, and track location, which could be found in all versions of Android, including Android 10.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] The vulnerability came by exploiting a bug in the multitasking system enabling a malicious app to overlay legitimate apps with fake login screens that users are not aware of when handing in security credentials.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Users can also be tricked into granting additional permissions to the malicious apps, which later enable them to perform various nefarious activities, including intercepting texts or calls and stealing banking credentials.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] *Avast Threat Labs* also discovered that many pre-installed apps on several hundred new Android devices contain dangerous malware and adware.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Some of the preinstalled malware can commit ad fraud or even take over its host device.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] In 2020, the Which? watchdog reported that more than a billion Android devices released in 2012 or earlier, which was 40% of Android devices worldwide, were at risk of being hacked.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] This conclusion stemmed from the fact that no security updates were issued for the Android versions below 7.0 in 2019.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Which? collaborated with the AV Comparatives anti-virus lab to infect five phone models with malware, and it succeeded in each case.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Google refused to comment on the watchdog's speculations.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] On August 5, 2020, Twitter published a blog urging its users to update their applications to the latest version with regards to a security concern that allowed others to access direct messages.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] A hacker could easily use the "Android system permissions" to fetch the account credentials in order to do so.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] The security issue is only with Android 8 (Android Oreo) and Android 9 (Android Pie).
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Twitter confirmed that updating the app will restrict such practices.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Android applications run in a sandbox, an isolated area of the system that does not have access to the rest of the system's resources, unless access permissions are explicitly granted by the user when the application is installed, however this may not be possible for pre-installed apps.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] It is not possible, for example, to turn off the microphone access of the pre-installed camera app without disabling the camera completely.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] This is valid also in Android versions 7 and 8.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Since February 2012, Google has used its Google Bouncer malware scanner to watch over and scan apps available in the Google Play store.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] A "Verify Apps" feature was introduced in November 2012, as part of the Android 4.2 "Jelly Bean" operating system version, to scan all apps, both from Google Play and from third-party sources, for malicious behaviour.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Originally only doing so during installation, Verify Apps received an update in 2014 to "constantly" scan apps, and in 2017 the feature was made visible to users through a menu in Settings.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] In former Android versions, before installing an application, the Google Play store displayed a list of the requirements an app needs to function.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] After reviewing these permissions, the user could choose to accept or refuse them, installing the application only if they accepted.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] In Android 6.0 "Marshmallow", the permissions system was changed; apps are no longer automatically granted all of their specified permissions at installation time.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] An opt-in system is used instead, in which users are prompted to grant or deny individual permissions to an app when they are needed for the first time.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Applications remember the grants, which can be revoked by the user at any time.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Pre-installed apps, however, are not always part of this approach.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] In some cases it may not be possible to deny certain permissions to pre-installed apps, nor be possible to disable them.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] The Google Play Services app cannot be uninstalled, nor disabled.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Any force stop attempt results in the app restarting itself.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] The new permissions model is used only by applications developed for Marshmallow using its software development kit (SDK), and older apps will continue to use the previous all-or-nothing approach.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Permissions can still be revoked for those apps, though this might prevent them from working properly, and a warning is displayed to that effect.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] In September 2014, Jason Nova of *Android Authority* reported on a study by the German security company Fraunhofer AISEC in antivirus software and malware threats on Android.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Nova wrote that "The Android operating system deals with software packages by sandboxing them; this does not allow applications to list the directory contents of other apps to keep the system safe.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] By not allowing the antivirus to list the directories of other apps after installation, applications that show no inherent suspicious behavior when downloaded are cleared as safe.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] If then later on parts of the app are activated that turn out to be malicious, the antivirus will have no way to know since it is inside the app and out of the antivirus' jurisdiction".
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] In August 2013, Google announced Android Device Manager (renamed Find My Device in May 2017), a service that allows users to remotely track, locate, and wipe their Android device, with an Android app for the service released in December.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] In December 2016, Google introduced a Trusted Contacts app, letting users request location-tracking of loved ones during emergencies.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] In 2020, Trusted Contacts was shut down and the location-sharing feature rolled into Google Maps.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] On October 8, 2018, Google announced new Google Play store requirements to combat oversharing of potentially sensitive information, including call and text logs.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] The issue stems from the fact that many apps request permissions to access users' personal information, even if this information is not needed for the app to function, and some users unquestionably grant these permissions.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Alternatively, a permission might be listed in the app manifest as required (as opposed to optional) and the app would not install unless user grants the permission; users can withdraw any, even required, permissions from any app in the device settings after app installation, but few users do this.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Google promised to work with developers and create exceptions if their apps require phone or SMS permissions for core functionality.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] The enforcement of this policy began on January 6, 2019, 90 days after its announcement.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Furthermore, Google announced a new "target API level requirement" (`targetSdkVersion` in manifest) of at least Android 8.0 (API level 26) for all new apps and app updates.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] The API level requirement was intended to combat the practice of app developers bypassing some permission screens by specifying early Android versions that had a coarser permission model.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] The Android Open Source Project implements a verified boot chain with intentions to verify that executed code, such as the kernel or bootloader, comes from an official source instead of a malicious actor.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] This implementation establishes a full chain of trust, as it initially starts at a hardware level.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Subsequently, the boot loader is verified and system partitions such as `system` and `vendor` are checked for integrity.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Furthermore, this process verifies that a previous version of Android has not been installed.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] This effectively provides rollback protection, which mitigates exploits that are similar to a downgrade attack.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Android (all supported versions, as far back as version 4.4 of the Android Open Source Project) has the option to provide a verified boot chain with `dm-verity`.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] This is a feature in the Linux kernel that allows for transparent integrity checking of block devices.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] This feature is designed to mitigate persistent rootkits.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Dependence on proprietary Google Play Services and customizations added on top of the operating system by vendors who license Android from Google is causing privacy concerns.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] In 2019, Google was fined €50 million by the French CNIL for a lack of information regarding their users.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Two years later, in 2021, researcher Douglas Leith, using a sort of data interception, showed that several data are sent from Android device to Google's servers, even when the phone is sleeping (IDLE) with no Google account registered into it.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Several Google applications send data, such as Chrome, Message or Docs, however YouTube is the only one to add a unique identifier data.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] In 2022, Leith showed that an Android phone sent various data related to communications, including phone and text messages to Google.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Timestamp, sender and receiver, plus several other data, are sent to Google Play Services infrastructure, even if the "Usage and Diag" feature is disabled.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Those data are marked with a Unique Identifier of an Android device, and do not comply with GDPR.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] In 2022, Google was sanctioned A$60 Million (US$40 million) by the Federal Court of Australia for misleading consumers about Google's collection of location data from Android phones.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] The ACCC estimates that around 1.3 million Australian Google account owners were impacted by this design.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Google has since taken remedial steps to address the behavior.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] A similar case to the 2019 French case regarding location tracking, was brought in the U.S. in a privacy lawsuit filed by a coalition of attorneys general from 40 U.S. states.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] A penalty of USD 391 Million was agreed between Google and the DoJ.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] The New York Times released at that time a long-term investigation about those privacy concerns.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Android devices, particularly low-end and mid-range models, have been criticized for their short software support lifespans.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Starting in the 2010s, many users found that their devices received only one or two major updates and a limited number of security patches.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] This lack of long-term support stemmed from manufacturers' unwillingness to invest in costly software upgrades, which were often tied to contractual agreements with chipset suppliers like Qualcomm.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] As a result, Android developed a reputation for rapid device obsolescence.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] To address this concern, Google introduced Project Treble, a framework designed to streamline the development and deployment of Android updates via Google Play Services, reducing manufacturers' involvement in the update process.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] However, for many devices, significant improvements were still limited by the chipset manufacturers.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Fairphone, a company focused on sustainability, explained that its inability to extend software support was due to Qualcomm's policies rather than its own.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Apple executives also highlighted Android's fragmented update ecosystem in their critiques of the platform, while quietly admitting that Qualcomm had also made it difficult for them to offer updates to the iPhone.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] In response to this problem, several community-driven initiatives emerged to provide alternative operating systems for unsupported devices including LineageOS, Sailfish OS, Ubuntu Touch, and PostmarketOS.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Starting in 2022, Samsung, the largest Android smartphone manufacturer, announced extended software support from previous two years, first to four years, followed by five years in 2023 and six years in 2024.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Shortly thereafter, Qualcomm followed suit, offering extending support timelines for OEM building phones with its chipsets, first to seven years in 2024, followed by eight years in 2025.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] However, the support commitment was only for its most powerful chipsets, and did not make a similar commitment for chipsets used in low-end and mid-range phones.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] These changes bring Samsung and potentially some Qualcomm-powered devices closer to competing platforms, such as Apple, whose iPhones have received four to eight years of support.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] In 2025, Google announced that all developers must register under its developer program in order to distribute applications on certified Android phones, whether it is done through the Play Store, sideloaded APKs, or third-party stores like F-Droid, citing security reasons.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] This measure will be effective starting September 2026.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] The measure will not directly affect degoogled custom ROMs, such as GrapheneOS.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] Google has faced a backlash by experts, developers, activists, lawyers and other groups, which founded the Keep Android Open initiative to raise awareness and signed an open letter urging Google to rescind the policy.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] They argue that Google will become a gatekeeper as it will be able to decide which apps can be installed and which others will not, provided that "sideloading" will be considerably tampered by the measure (at least 9 steps needed and it would imply waiting 24 hours before an install).
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p02] They also criticize that it creates "an ever-expanding pathway to internet censorship" alleging more centralization of power.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] The source code for Android is open-source: it is developed in private by Google, with the source code released publicly when a new version of Android is released.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Google publishes most of the code (including network and telephony stacks) under the non-copyleft Apache License version 2.0. which allows modification and redistribution.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] The license does not grant rights to the "Android" trademark, so device manufacturers and wireless carriers have to license it from Google under individual contracts.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Associated Linux kernel changes are released under the copyleft GNU General Public License version 2, developed by the Open Handset Alliance, with the source code publicly available at all times.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] The only Android release which was not immediately made available as source code was the tablet-only 3.0 *Honeycomb* release.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] The reason, according to Andy Rubin in an official Android blog post, was because *Honeycomb* was rushed for production of the Motorola Xoom, and they did not want third parties creating a "really bad user experience" by attempting to put onto smartphones a version of Android intended for tablets.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] These applications must be licensed from Google by device makers, and can only be shipped on devices which meet its compatibility guidelines and other requirements.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Custom, certified distributions of Android produced by manufacturers (such as Samsung Experience) may also replace certain stock Android apps with their own proprietary variants and add additional software not included in the stock Android operating system.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] With the advent of the Google Pixel line of devices, Google itself has also made specific Android features timed or permanent exclusives to the Pixel series.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] There may also be "binary blob" drivers required for certain hardware components in the device.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] The best known fully open source Android services are the LineageOS distribution and MicroG which acts as an open source replacement of Google Play Services.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] In both cases, the use of closed-source software causes the system to become vulnerable to backdoors.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] It has been argued that because developers are often required to purchase the Google-branded Android license, this has turned the theoretically open system into a freemium service.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Google licenses their Google Mobile Services software, along with the Android trademarks, only to hardware manufacturers for devices that meet Google's compatibility standards specified in the Android Compatibility Program document.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Thus, forks of Android that make major changes to the operating system itself do not include any of Google's non-free components, stay incompatible with applications that require them, and must ship with an alternative software marketplace in lieu of Google Play Store.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] A prominent example of such an Android fork is Amazon's Fire OS, which is used on the Kindle Fire line of tablets, and oriented toward Amazon services.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] The shipment of Android devices without GMS is also common in mainland China, as Google does not do business there.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] In 2014, Google also began to require that all Android devices which license the Google Mobile Services software display a prominent "Powered by Android" logo on their boot screens.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] In March 2018, it was reported that Google had begun to block "uncertified" Android devices from using Google Mobile Services software, and display a warning indicating that "the device manufacturer has preloaded Google apps and services without certification from Google".
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Users of custom ROMs can register their device ID to their Google account to remove this block.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Moreover, open-source variants of some applications also exclude functions that are present in their non-free versions.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Apps that do not use Google components would also be at a functional disadvantage, as they can only use APIs contained within the OS itself.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] In turn, third-party apps may have dependencies on Google Play Services.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Alibaba Group defended the allegations, arguing that the OS was a distinct platform from Android (primarily using HTML5 apps), but incorporated portions of Android's platform to allow backwards compatibility with third-party Android software.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Indeed, the devices did ship with an application store which offered Android apps; however, the majority of them were pirated.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Android received a lukewarm reaction when it was unveiled in 2007.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Although analysts were impressed with the respected technology companies that had partnered with Google to form the Open Handset Alliance, it was unclear whether mobile phone manufacturers would be willing to replace their existing operating systems with Android.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] The idea of an open-source, Linux-based development platform sparked interest, but there were additional worries about Android facing strong competition from established players in the smartphone market, such as Nokia and Microsoft, and rival Linux mobile operating systems that were in development.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Since then Android has grown to become the most widely used smartphone operating system and "one of the fastest mobile experiences available".
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] As a result, it has been described by technology website *Ars Technica* as "practically the default operating system for launching new hardware" for companies without their own mobile platforms.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] This openness and flexibility is also present at the level of the end user: Android allows extensive customisation of devices by their owners and apps are freely available from non-Google app stores and third party websites.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] These have been cited as among the main advantages of Android phones over others.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Despite Android's popularity, including an activation rate three times that of iOS, there have been reports that Google has not been able to leverage their other products and web services successfully to turn Android into the money maker that analysts had expected.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] In 2014, in an effort to improve prominence of the Android brand, Google began to require that devices featuring its proprietary components display an Android logo on the boot screen.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] For example, according to data from OpenSignal in July 2013, there were 11,868 models of Android devices, numerous screen sizes and eight Android OS versions simultaneously in use, while the large majority of iOS users have upgraded to the latest iteration of that OS.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Critics such as *Apple Insider* have asserted that fragmentation via hardware and software pushed Android's growth through large volumes of low end, budget-priced devices running older versions of Android.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] They maintain this forces Android developers to write for the "lowest common denominator" to reach as many users as possible, who have too little incentive to make use of the latest hardware or software features only available on a smaller percentage of devices.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] However, OpenSignal, who develops both Android and iOS apps, concluded that although fragmentation can make development trickier, Android's wider global reach also increases the potential reward.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Android is the largest mobile OS with 76% market share as of Q1 2025.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Android is the most used operating system on phones in many countries, with some countries, such as India, having over 96% market share.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] On tablets, usage is more even, as iOS is a bit more popular globally.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Research company Canalys estimated in the second quarter of 2009, that Android had a 2.8% share of worldwide smartphone shipments.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] By May 2010, Android had a 10% worldwide smartphone market share, overtaking Windows Mobile, whilst in the US Android held a 28% share, overtaking iPhone OS.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] By the fourth quarter of 2010, its worldwide share had grown to 33% of the market becoming the top-selling smartphone platform, overtaking Symbian.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] In the US it became the top-selling platform in April 2011, overtaking BlackBerry OS with a 31.2% smartphone share, according to *comScore*.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] By the third quarter of 2011, Gartner estimated that more than half (52.5%) of the smartphone sales belonged to Android.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] By the third quarter of 2012 Android had a 75% share of the global smartphone market according to the research firm IDC.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] In July 2011, Google said that 550,000 Android devices were being activated every day, up from 400,000 per day in May, and more than 100 million devices had been activated with 4.4% growth per week.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] In September 2012, 500 million devices had been activated with 1.3 million activations per day.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] In May 2013, at Google I/O, Sundar Pichai announced that 900 million Android devices had been activated.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Android market share varies by location.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] In July 2012, "mobile subscribers aged 13+" in the United States using Android were up to 52%, and rose to 90% in China.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] During the third quarter of 2012, Android's worldwide smartphone shipment market share was 75%, with 750 million devices activated in total.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] In April 2013, Android had 1.5 million activations per day.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] As of May 2013, 48 billion application ("app") installation have been performed from the Google Play store, and by September 2013, one billion Android devices had been activated.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] As of August 2020, the Google Play store had over 3 million Android applications published, and as of May 2016, apps had been downloaded more than 65 billion times.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] The operating system's success has made it a target for patent litigation as part of the so-called "smartphone wars" between technology companies.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Android devices account for more than half of smartphone sales in most markets, including the US, while "only in Japan was Apple on top" (September–November 2013 numbers).
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] At the end of 2013, over 1.5 billion Android smartphones had been sold in the four years since 2010, making Android the most sold phone and tablet OS.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Three billion Android smartphones were estimated to be sold by the end of 2014 (including previous years).
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] According to Gartner research company, Android-based devices outsold all contenders, every year since 2012.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] In 2013, it outsold Windows 2.8:1 or by 573 million.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] As of 2015, Android has the largest installed base of all operating systems; Since 2013, devices running it also sell more than Windows, iOS and Mac OS X devices combined.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] According to StatCounter, which tracks only the use for browsing the web, Android is the most popular mobile operating system since August 2013.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Android is the most popular operating system for web browsing in India and several other countries (e.g. virtually all of Asia, with Japan and North Korea exceptions).
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Gartner expected the whole mobile phone market to "reach two billion units in 2016", including Android.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] According to a Statistica's estimate, Android smartphones had an installed base of 1.8 billion units in 2015, which was 76% of the estimated total number of smartphones worldwide.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Android has the largest installed base of any mobile operating system and, since 2013, the highest-selling operating system overall with sales in 2012, 2013 and 2014 close to the installed base of all PCs.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] In the second quarter of 2014, Android's share of the global smartphone shipment market was 84.7%, a new record.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] This had grown to 87.5% worldwide market share by the third quarter of 2016, leaving main competitor iOS with 12.1% market share.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] According to an April 2017 StatCounter report, Android overtook Microsoft Windows to become the most popular operating system for total Internet usage.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] It has maintained the plurality since then.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] In September 2015, Google announced that Android had 1.4 billion monthly active users.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] This changed to 2 billion monthly active users in May 2017.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Despite its success on smartphones, initially Android tablet adoption was slow, then later caught up with the iPad, in most countries.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] One of the main causes was the chicken or the egg situation where consumers were hesitant to buy an Android tablet due to a lack of high quality tablet applications, but developers were hesitant to spend time and resources developing tablet applications until there was a significant market for them.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] The content and app "ecosystem" proved more important than hardware specs as the selling point for tablets.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Due to the lack of Android tablet-specific applications in 2011, early Android tablets had to make do with existing smartphone applications that were ill-suited to larger screen sizes, whereas the dominance of Apple's iPad was reinforced by the large number of tablet-specific iOS applications.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Despite app support in its infancy, a considerable number of Android tablets, like the Barnes & Noble Nook (alongside those using other operating systems, such as the HP TouchPad and BlackBerry PlayBook) were rushed out to market in an attempt to capitalize on the success of the iPad.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] This approach, such as with the Dell Streak, failed to gain market traction with consumers as well as damaging the early reputation of Android tablets.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Furthermore, several Android tablets such as the Motorola Xoom were priced the same or higher than the iPad, which hurt sales.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] An exception was the Amazon Kindle Fire, which relied upon lower pricing as well as access to Amazon's ecosystem of applications and content.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] This began to change in 2012, with the release of the affordable Nexus 7 and a push by Google for developers to write better tablet applications.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] According to International Data Corporation, shipments of Android-powered tablets surpassed iPads in Q3 2012.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] As of the end of 2013, over 191.6 million Android tablets had sold in three years since 2011.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] This made Android tablets the most-sold type of tablet in 2013, surpassing iPads in the second quarter of 2013.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] According to StatCounter's web use statistics, as of 2020, Android tablets represent the majority of tablet devices used in Africa (70%), South America (65%), while less than half elsewhere, e.g.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] There are countries on all continents where Android tablets are the majority, for example, Mexico.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] India, and in Europe, with some notable exceptions such as the US (iPadOS 57%), and in China (iPadOS 53%)).
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Of all operating systems Android is first at 37%, followed by Windows at 28%, then iOS/iPadOS at 18%.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] The latest version Android 16 is the most popular Android version on smartphones and Android 14 on tablets.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] As of April 2026, the latest version Android 16 is most popular Android version on smartphones at 22%, followed by Android 15 (at 19%, down from 30% peak), 13, 14, 12 and 11.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Android is more used than iOS is virtually all countries, with few exceptions such as iOS has a 58% share in the US.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Android 16 is the most-used version in e.g.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] US, Europe, China, and Japan and Android 15 in India.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Usage of Android 13 and newer, i.e. supported versions, is at 69%, the rest of users are not supported with security updates; with recently supported Android 12 (last security updates in 2025), use is at 79%.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] On tablets, Android 14 is the most popular version overall (also in e.g.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] India, Russia, Canada, Australia, Europe and South America), at 19%.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Usage of Android 13 and newer, i.e. supported versions, is at 48.2% on Android tablets, and with Android 12, until recently supported, at 56.7%.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] The usage share varies a lot by country.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] 73% of US users use insecure Android tablets, and 78% of UK users, and the very old Android 9.0 Pie is still the most commonly used tablet version in both countries.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Paid Android applications in the past were simple to pirate.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] In a May 2012 interview with *Eurogamer*, the developers of *Football Manager* stated that the ratio of pirated players vs legitimate players was 9:1 for their game *Football Manager Handheld*.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] However, not every developer agreed that piracy rates were an issue; for example, in July 2012 the developers of the game *Wind-up Knight* said that piracy levels of their game were only 12%, and most of the piracy came from China, where people cannot purchase apps from Google Play.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] In 2010, Google released a tool for validating authorized purchases for use within apps, but developers complained that this was insufficient and trivial to crack.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Google responded that the tool, especially its initial release, was intended as a sample framework for developers to modify and build upon depending on their needs, not as a finished piracy solution.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Android "Jelly Bean" introduced the ability for paid applications to be encrypted, so that they may work only on the device for which they were purchased.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Android has been the subject of various cases of patent, copyright, and antitrust litigation.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] On August 12, 2010, Oracle sued Google over claimed infringement of copyrights and patents related to the Java programming language.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Oracle originally sought damages up to $6.1 billion, but this valuation was rejected by a United States federal judge who asked Oracle to revise the estimate.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] In response, Google submitted multiple lines of defense, counterclaiming that Android did not infringe on Oracle's patents or copyright, that Oracle's patents were invalid, and several other defenses.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] They said that Android's Java runtime environment is based on Apache Harmony, a clean room implementation of the Java class libraries, and an independently developed virtual machine called Dalvik.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] In May 2012, the jury in this case found that Google did not infringe on Oracle's patents, and the trial judge ruled that the structure of the Java APIs used by Google was not copyrightable.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] The parties agreed to zero dollars in statutory damages for a small amount of copied code.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] On May 9, 2014, the Federal Circuit partially reversed the district court ruling, ruling in Oracle's favor on the copyrightability issue, and remanding the issue of fair use to the district court.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] In December 2015, Google announced that the next major release of Android (Android Nougat) would switch to OpenJDK, which is the official open-source implementation of the Java platform, instead of using the now-discontinued Apache Harmony project as its runtime.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Code reflecting this change was also posted to the AOSP source repository.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] In its announcement, Google claimed this was part of an effort to create a "common code base" between Java on Android and other platforms.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] In June 2016, a United States federal court ruled in favor of Google, stating that its use of the APIs was fair use.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] In April 2021, the Supreme Court of the United States ruled that Google's use of the Java APIs was within the bounds of fair use, reversing the Federal Circuit Appeals Court ruling and remanding the case for further hearing.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] The majority opinion began with the assumption that the APIs may be copyrightable, and thus proceeded with a review of the factors that contributed to fair use.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] In addition to lawsuits against Google directly, various proxy wars have been waged against Android indirectly by targeting manufacturers of Android devices, with the effect of discouraging manufacturers from adopting the platform by increasing the costs of bringing an Android device to market.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Both Apple and Microsoft have sued several manufacturers for patent infringement, with Apple's legal action against Samsung being a particularly high-profile case.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] In January 2012, Microsoft said they had signed patent license agreements with eleven Android device manufacturers, whose products account for "70 percent of all Android smartphones" sold in the US and 55% of the worldwide revenue for Android devices.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Samsung's patent settlement with Microsoft included an agreement to allocate more resources to developing and marketing phones running Microsoft's Windows Phone operating system.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Microsoft has also tied its own Android software to patent licenses, requiring the bundling of Microsoft Office Mobile and Skype applications on Android devices to subsidize the licensing fees, while at the same time helping to promote its software lines.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Google has publicly expressed its frustration for the current patent landscape in the United States, accusing Apple, Oracle and Microsoft of trying to take down Android through patent litigation, rather than innovating and competing with better products and services.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] In August 2011, Google purchased Motorola Mobility for US$12.5 billion, which was viewed in part as a defensive measure to protect Android, since Motorola Mobility held more than 17,000 patents.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] In December 2011, Google bought over a thousand patents from IBM.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] In 2013, FairSearch, a lobbying organization supported by Microsoft, Oracle and others, filed a complaint regarding Android with the European Commission, alleging that its free-of-charge distribution model constituted anti-competitive predatory pricing.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] The Free Software Foundation Europe, whose donors include Google, disputed the Fairsearch allegations.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] In August 2016, Google was fined US$6.75 million by the Russian Federal Antimonopoly Service (FAS) under similar allegations by Yandex.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] The EU fined Google for €4.3 billion (about US$5 billion) and required the company to end this conduct within 90 days.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Google filed its appeal of the ruling in October 2018, though will not ask for any interim measures to delay the onset of conduct requirements.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] On October 16, 2018, Google announced that it would change its distribution model for Google Mobile Services in the EU, since part of its revenues streams for Android which came through use of Google Search and Chrome were now prohibited by the EU's ruling.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] While the core Android system remains free, OEMs in Europe would be required to purchase a paid license to the core suite of Google applications, such as Gmail, Google Maps and the Google Play Store.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Google Search will be licensed separately, with an option to include Google Chrome at no additional cost atop Search.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] European OEMs can bundle third-party alternatives on phones and devices sold to customers, if they so choose.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] OEMs will no longer be barred from selling any device running incompatible versions of Android in Europe.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Turkey's competition authority began investigating the default Android search engine in 2017, leading to a US$17.4 million fine in September 2018 and a fine of 0.05 percent of Google's revenue per day in November 2019 when Google did not meet the requirements.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] In December 2019, Google stopped issuing licenses for new Android phone models sold in Turkey.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] In September 2021, the Fair Trade Commission (South Korea) fined Google $177 million for restricting manufacturers, such as Samsung Electronics, from using modified versions of Android.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] In 2025, the Competition Commission of India charged Google for "mandatory preinstallation of Google Play Store and other applications" on Android TV.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Google settled, unbundling the services and paying a $2.38 million fine.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Google has developed several variations of Android for specific use cases, including Android Wear, later renamed Wear OS, for wearable devices such as wrist watches, Android TV for televisions, Android Things for smart or Internet of things devices and Android Automotive for cars.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Additionally, by providing infrastructure that combines dedicated hardware and dedicated applications running on regular Android, Google have opened up the platform for its use in particular usage scenarios, such as the Android Auto app for cars, and Daydream, a Virtual Reality platform.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Additionally, Android has been installed and run on a variety of less-technical objects, including calculators, single-board computers, feature phones, electronic dictionaries, alarm clocks, refrigerators, landline telephones, coffee machines, bicycles, and mirrors.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Ouya, a video game console running Android, became one of the most successful Kickstarter campaigns, crowdfunding US$8.5m for its development, and was later followed by other Android-based consoles, such as Nvidia's Shield Portable – an Android device in a video game controller form factor.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] In 2011, Google demonstrated "Android@Home", a home automation technology which uses Android to control a range of household devices including light switches, power sockets and thermostats.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Prototype light bulbs were announced that could be controlled from an Android phone or tablet, but Android head Andy Rubin was cautious to note that "turning a lightbulb on and off is nothing new", pointing to numerous failed home automation services.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Google, he said, was thinking more ambitiously and the intention was to use their position as a cloud services provider to bring Google products into customers' homes.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Parrot unveiled an Android-based car stereo system known as Asteroid in 2011, followed by a successor, the touchscreen-based Asteroid Smart, in 2012.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] In 2013, Clarion released its own Android-based car stereo, the AX1.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Android comes preinstalled on a few laptops (a similar functionality of running Android applications is also available in Google's ChromeOS) and can also be installed on personal computers by end users.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] On those platforms Android provides additional functionality for physical keyboards and mice, together with the "Alt-Tab" key combination for switching applications quickly with a keyboard.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] In December 2014, one reviewer commented that Android's notification system is "vastly more complete and robust than in most environments" and that Android is "absolutely usable" as one's primary desktop operating system.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] In October 2015, *The Wall Street Journal* reported that Android will serve as Google's future main laptop operating system, with the plan to fold ChromeOS into it by 2017.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] That is unlike Android where support is shorter with "EOL dates [being..] at least 3 years [into the future] for Android tablets for education".
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] At Google I/O in May 2016, Google announced Daydream, a virtual reality platform that relied on a smartphone and provided VR capabilities through a virtual reality headset and controller designed by Google itself.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] However, this did not catch on and was discontinued in 2019.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] The mascot of Android is a green android robot, as related to the software's name.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Although it had no official name for a long time, the Android team at Google reportedly call it "Bugdroid".
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] In 2024, a Google blog post revealed its official name, "The Bot".
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] It was designed by then-Google graphic designer Irina Blok on November 5, 2007, when Android was announced.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Contrary to reports that she was tasked with a project to create an icon, Blok confirmed in an interview that she independently developed it and made it open source.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] The robot design was initially not presented to Google, but it quickly became commonplace in the Android development team, with various variations of it created by the developers there who liked the figure, as it was free under a Creative Commons license.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-operating-system-p03] Its popularity amongst the development team eventually led to Google adopting it as an official icon as part of the Android logo when it launched to consumers in 2008.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] It was initially unveiled as an alpha quality developer preview in March 2017 and later made available to the public on August 21, 2017.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] It contains several major features, including notification channels, picture-in-picture support for video, performance improvements, and battery usage optimization, and support for autofillers, Bluetooth 5, system-level integration with VoIP apps, wide color gamuts, and Wi-Fi Aware.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] Android Oreo also introduces two major platform features: Android Go – a software distribution of the operating system for low-end devices – and support for implementing a hardware abstraction layer.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] Android Oreo was discontinued and no longer received security updates after October 2021.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] Android Oreo was internally codenamed "Oatmeal Cookie." On March 21, 2017, Google released the first developer preview of Android "O", available for the Nexus 5X, Nexus 6P, Nexus Player, Pixel C, and both Pixel smartphones.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] The second, considered beta quality, was released on May 17, 2017.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] The third developer preview was released on June 8, 2017, and offered a finalized version of the API.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] On July 24, 2017, a fourth developer preview was released, which included the final system behaviors and the latest bug fixes and optimizations.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] Android "O" was officially released on August 21, 2017, under the name "Oreo", after the Oreo brand of sandwich cookie.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] Its lawn statue was unveiled at a promotional event across from Chelsea Market in New York City—a building which formerly housed a Nabisco factory where Oreo cookies were first produced.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] Factory images were made available for compatible Pixel and Nexus devices later that day.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] The Sony Xperia XZ1 and Sony Xperia XZ1 Compact were the first devices available with Oreo pre-installed.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] Android 8.1 was released in December 2017 for Pixel and Nexus devices, which features minor bug fixes and user interface changes.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] Notifications can be snoozed, and batched into topic-based groups known as "channels".
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] The 'Major Ongoing' feature orders the alerts by priority, pinning the most important application to the top slot.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] Android Oreo contains integrated support for picture-in-picture modes.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] The "Settings" app features a new design which has been reduced in size, with a white theme and deeper categorization of different settings, while its ringtone, alarm and notification sound settings now contain an option for adding custom sounds to the list.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] The Android 8.1 update supports the display of battery percentages for connected Bluetooth devices, makes the notification shade slightly translucent, and dims the on-screen navigation keys to reduce the possibility of burn-in.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] Notification alert sounds are also limited to one per second for each app.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] Android Runtime (ART) features performance improvements.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] Android Oreo contains additional limits on apps' background activities to improve battery life.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] Apps can specify "adaptive icons" for differently-shaped containers specified by themes, such as circles, squares, and squircles.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] Android Oreo adds native support for Advanced Audio Coding, aptX, aptX HD and LDAC Bluetooth codecs.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] Android Oreo supports new emoji that were included in the Unicode 10 standard.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] A new emoji font was also introduced, which notably redesigns its face figures to use a traditional circular shape, as opposed to the "blob" design that was introduced on KitKat.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] Support for downloadable fonts was introduced in Android Oreo; this functionality is also available for older versions of Android via the AndroidX Core library.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] The Android architecture was revised so that low-level, vendor-specific code for supporting a device's hardware can be separated from the Android OS framework using a hardware abstraction layer known as the "vendor interface".
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] Vendor interfaces must be forward-compatible with future versions of Android.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] This new architecture, called Project Treble, allows the quicker development and deployment of Android updates for devices, as vendors would only need to make the necessary modifications to their bundled software.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] All devices shipping with Oreo must support a vendor interface, but this feature is optional for devices being updated to Oreo from an earlier version.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] The "seamless updates" system introduced in Android 7.0 was also modified to download update files directly to the system partition, rather than requiring them to be downloaded to the user partition first.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] This reduces storage space requirements for system updates.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] Android Oreo introduces a new automatic repair system known as "Rescue Party"; if the operating system detects that core system components are persistently crashing during startup, it will automatically perform a series of escalating repair steps.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] If all automatic repair steps are exhausted, the device will reboot into recovery mode and prompt a factory reset.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] A tailored distribution for low-end devices known as Android Go was unveiled for Oreo; it is intended for devices with 1 GB of RAM or less.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] This mode includes platform optimizations to reduce mobile data usage (including enabling Data Saver mode by default) and a special suite of Google Mobile Services designed to be less resource- and bandwidth-intensive.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] The Google Play Store would also highlight lightweight apps suited for these devices.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] Google Play Services was also modularized to reduce its memory footprint.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] Android Go was made available to OEMs for Android 8.1.
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] Android Oreo rebrands multiple security features provided by Google Play Services under the blanket name "Google Play Protect", including automatic scanning of Google Play Store and sideloaded apps, and Android Device Manager, which is now branded as "Find My Device".
[src:hardware-abstraction/android-oreo] A verified boot now includes a "Rollback Protection" feature that prevents rolling back the device to a previous version of Android, aimed at preventing a potential thief from bypassing security measures by installing a previous version of the operating system that doesn't have them in place.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] An **application programming interface** (**API**) is a connection between computers or between computer programs.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] It is a type of software interface, offering a service to other pieces of software.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] A document or standard that describes how to build such a connection or interface is called an *API specification*.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] A computer system that meets this standard is said to *implement* or *expose* an API.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] The term API may refer either to the specification or to the implementation.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] In contrast to a user interface, which connects a computer to a person, an application programming interface connects computers or pieces of software to each other.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] It is not intended to be used directly by a person (the end user) other than a computer programmer who is incorporating it into software.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] An API is often made up of different parts which act as tools or services that are available to the programmer.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] A program or a programmer that uses one of these parts is said to *call* that portion of the API.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] The calls that make up the API are also known as subroutines, methods, requests, or endpoints.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] An API specification *defines* these calls, meaning that it explains how to use or implement them.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] One of the main purpose of APIs is to hide the internal details of how a system works, exposing only those parts a programmer will find useful and keeping them consistent even if the internal details later change.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] An API may be custom-built for a particular pair of systems, or it may be a shared standard allowing interoperability among many systems.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] The term API is often used to refer to web APIs, which allow communication between computers that are joined by the internet.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] There are also APIs for programming languages, software libraries, computer operating systems, and computer hardware.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] APIs originated in the 1940s, though the term did not emerge until the 1960s and 70s.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] An API opens a software system to interactions from the outside.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] It allows two software systems to communicate across a boundary — an interface — using mutually agreed-upon signals.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] In other words, an API connects software entities together.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Unlike a user interface, an API is typically not visible to users.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] It is an "under the hood" portion of a software system, used for machine-to-machine communication.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] A well-designed API exposes only objects or actions needed by software or software developers.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] This abstraction simplifies programming.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Building software using APIs has been compared to using building-block toys, such as Lego bricks.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Software services or software libraries are analogous to the bricks; they may be joined together via their APIs, composing a new software product.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] The process of joining is called *integration*.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] As an example, consider a weather sensor that offers an API.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] When a certain message is transmitted to the sensor, it will detect the current weather conditions and reply with a weather report.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] The message that activates the sensor is an API *call*, and the weather report is an API *response*.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] A weather forecasting app might integrate with a number of weather sensor APIs, gathering weather data from throughout a geographical area.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] It represents an agreement between parties: a service provider who offers the API and the software developers who rely upon it.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] If the API remains stable, or if it changes only in predictable ways, developers' confidence in the API will increase.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] The term *API* initially described an interface only for end-user-facing programs, known as application programs.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] This origin is still reflected in the name "application programming interface." Today, the term is broader, including also utility software and even hardware interfaces.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] The idea of the API is much older than the term itself.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] British computer scientists Maurice Wilkes and David Wheeler worked on a modular software library in the 1940s for EDSAC, an early computer.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] The subroutines in this library were stored on punched paper tape organized in a filing cabinet.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] This cabinet also contained what Wilkes and Wheeler called a "library catalog" of notes about each subroutine and how to incorporate it into a program.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Today, such a catalog would be called an API (or an API specification or API documentation) because it instructs a programmer on how to use (or "call") each subroutine that the programmer needs.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Wilkes and Wheeler's book *The Preparation of Programs for an Electronic Digital Computer* contains the first published API specification.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Joshua Bloch considers that Wilkes and Wheeler "latently invented" the API, because it is more of a concept that is discovered than invented.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] The term "application program interface" (without an *-ing* suffix) is first recorded in a paper called *Data structures and techniques for remote computer graphics* presented at an AFIPS conference in 1968.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] The authors of this paper use the term to describe the interaction of an application—a graphics program in this case—with the rest of the computer system.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] A consistent application interface (consisting of Fortran subroutine calls) was intended to free the programmer from dealing with idiosyncrasies of the graphics display device, and to provide hardware independence if the computer or the display were replaced.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] The term was introduced to the field of databases by C.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Date in a 1974 paper called *The Relational and Network Approaches: Comparison of the Application Programming Interface*.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] An API became a part of the ANSI/SPARC framework for database management systems.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] This framework treated the application programming interface separately from other interfaces, such as the query interface.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Database professionals in the 1970s observed these different interfaces could be combined; a sufficiently rich application interface could support the other interfaces as well.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] This observation led to APIs that supported all types of programming, not just application programming.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] By 1990, the API was defined simply as "a set of services available to a programmer for performing certain tasks" by technologist Carl Malamud.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] The idea of the API was expanded again with the dawn of remote procedure calls and web APIs.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] As computer networks became common in the 1970s and 80s, programmers wanted to call libraries located not only on their local computers, but on computers located elsewhere.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] These remote procedure calls were well supported by the Java language in particular.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] In the 1990s, with the spread of the internet, standards like CORBA, COM, and DCOM competed to become the most common way to expose API services.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] XML and JSON web APIs saw widespread commercial adoption beginning in 2000 and continuing as of 2021.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] The web API is now the most common meaning of the term API.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] The Semantic Web proposed by Tim Berners-Lee in 2001 included "semantic APIs" that recast the API as an open, distributed data interface rather than a software behavior interface.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Proprietary interfaces and agents became more widespread than open ones, but the idea of the API as a data interface took hold.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Because web APIs are widely used to exchange data of all kinds online, API has become a broad term describing much of the communication on the internet.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] When used in this way, the term API has overlap in meaning with the term communication protocol.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] The interface to a software library is one type of API.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] The API describes and prescribes the "expected behavior" (a specification) while the library is an "actual implementation" of this set of rules.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] A single API can have multiple implementations (or none, being abstract) in the form of different libraries that share the same programming interface.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] The separation of the API from its implementation can allow programs written in one language to use a library written in another.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] For example, because Scala and Java compile to compatible bytecode, Scala developers can take advantage of any Java API.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] API use can vary depending on the type of programming language involved.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] An API for a procedural language such as Lua could consist primarily of basic routines to execute code, manipulate data or handle errors while an API for an object-oriented language, such as Java, would provide a specification of classes and its class methods.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] By mapping the features and capabilities of one language to an interface implemented in another language, a language binding allows a library or service written in one language to be used when developing in another language.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Tools such as SWIG and F2PY, a Fortran-to-Python interface generator, facilitate the creation of such interfaces.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Moreover, the overall program flow of control can be out of the control of the caller and in the framework's hands by inversion of control or a similar mechanism.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] An API can specify the interface between an application and the operating system.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] POSIX, for example, specifies a set of common APIs that aim to enable an application written for a POSIX conformant operating system to be compiled for another POSIX conformant operating system.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Linux and Berkeley Software Distribution are examples of operating systems that implement the POSIX APIs.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Microsoft has shown a strong commitment to a backward-compatible API, particularly within its Windows API (Win32) library, so older applications may run on newer versions of Windows using an executable-specific setting called "Compatibility Mode".
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] How much Microsoft developers' access to the company's operating systems' internal APIs is an advantage is unclear.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Shaffer of *Technologic Computer Letter* in 1987 compared the situation to a baseball game in which "Microsoft owns all the bats and the field", and large vendors like Lotus Development and Ashton-Tate reportedly received information about MS-DOS 5.0 that smaller software developers did not.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Ed Esber of Ashton-Tate said in a 1987 interview, however, that Bill Gates told him that his developers sometimes had to rewrite software based on early APIs.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Gates noted in the interview that Microsoft's Apple Macintosh applications were more successful than those for MS-DOS, because his company did not have to also devote resources to Mac OS.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] An API differs from an application binary interface (ABI) in that an API is source code based while an ABI is binary based.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] For instance, POSIX provides APIs while the Linux Standard Base provides an ABI.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Remote APIs allow developers to manipulate remote resources through protocols, specific standards for communication that allow different technologies to work together, regardless of language or platform.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Therefore, remote APIs are useful in maintaining the object abstraction in object-oriented programming; a method call, executed locally on a proxy object, invokes the corresponding method on the remote object, using the remoting protocol, and acquires the result to be used locally as a return value.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] A modification of the proxy object will also result in a corresponding modification of the remote object.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Web APIs are the defined interfaces through which interactions happen between an enterprise and applications that use its assets, which also is a Service Level Agreement (SLA) to specify the functional provider and expose the service path or URL for its API users.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] An API approach is an architectural approach that revolves around providing a program interface to a set of services to different applications serving different types of consumers.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] An example might be a shipping company API that can be added to an eCommerce-focused website to facilitate ordering shipping services and automatically include current shipping rates, without the site developer having to enter the shipper's rate table into a web database.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Part of this trend is related to the Semantic Web movement toward Resource Description Framework (RDF), a concept to promote web-based ontology engineering technologies.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Web APIs allow the combination of multiple APIs into new applications known as mashups.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] In the social media space, web APIs have allowed web communities to facilitate sharing content and data between communities and applications.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] In this way, content that is created in one place dynamically can be posted and updated to multiple locations on the web.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] For example, Twitter's REST API allows developers to access core Twitter data and the Search API provides methods for developers to interact with Twitter Search and trends data.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] The design of an API has significant impact on its usage.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] The principle of information hiding describes the role of programming interfaces as enabling modular programming by hiding the implementation details of the modules so that users of modules need not understand the complexities inside the modules.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Thus, the design of an API attempts to provide only the tools a user would expect.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] The design of programming interfaces represents an important part of software architecture, the organization of a complex piece of software.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] APIs are one of the more common ways technology companies integrate.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Those that provide and use APIs are considered as being members of a business ecosystem.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] An important factor when an API becomes public is its "interface stability".
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Changes to the API—for example adding new parameters to a function call—could break compatibility with the clients that depend on that API.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] When parts of a publicly presented API are subject to change and thus not stable, such parts of a particular API should be documented explicitly as "unstable".
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] For example, in the Google Guava library, the parts that are considered unstable, and that might change soon, are marked with the Java annotation `@Beta`.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] A public API can sometimes declare parts of itself as *deprecated* or rescinded.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] This usually means that part of the API should be considered a candidate for being removed, or modified in a backward incompatible way.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Therefore, these changes allow developers to transition away from parts of the API that will be removed or not supported in the future.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Client code may contain innovative or opportunistic usages that were not intended by the API designers.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] In other words, for a library with a significant user base, when an element becomes part of the public API, it may be used in diverse ways.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] On February 19, 2020, Akamai published their annual “State of the Internet” report, showcasing the growing trend of cybercriminals targeting public API platforms at financial services worldwide.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] From December 2017 through November 2019, Akamai witnessed 85.42 billion credential violation attacks.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] About 20%, or 16.55 billion, were against hostnames defined as API endpoints.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Of these, 473.5 million have targeted financial services sector organizations.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] API documentation describes what services an API offers and how to use those services, aiming to cover everything a client would need to know for practical purposes.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Documentation is crucial for the development and maintenance of applications using the API.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] API documentation is traditionally found in documentation files but can also be found in social media such as blogs, forums, and Q&A websites.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Traditional documentation files are often presented via a documentation system, such as Javadoc or Pydoc, that has a consistent appearance and structure.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] However, the types of content included in the documentation differs from API to API.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] In the interest of clarity, API documentation may include a description of classes and methods in the API as well as typical usage scenarios, code snippets, design rationales, performance discussions, and contracts, but implementation details of the API services themselves are usually omitted.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] It can take a number of forms, including instructional documents, tutorials, and reference works.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] It'll also include a variety of information types, including guides and functionalities.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Restrictions and limitations on how the API can be used are also covered by the documentation.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] For instance, documentation for an API function could note that its parameters cannot be null, that the function itself is not thread safe.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Because API documentation tends to be comprehensive, it is a challenge for writers to keep the documentation updated and for users to read it carefully, potentially yielding bugs.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] API documentation can be enriched with metadata information like Java annotations.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] This metadata can be used by the compiler, tools, and by the *run-time* environment to implement custom behaviors or custom handling.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] It is possible to generate API documentation in a data-driven manner.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] By observing many programs that use a given API, it is possible to infer the typical usages, as well the required contracts and directives.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Then, templates can be used to generate natural language from the mined data.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] In 2010, Oracle Corporation sued Google for having distributed a new implementation of Java embedded in the Android operating system.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Google had not acquired any permission to reproduce the Java API, although permission had been given to the similar OpenJDK project.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Judge William Alsup ruled in the *Oracle v.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Alsup's ruling was overturned in 2014 on appeal to the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit, though the question of whether such use of APIs constitutes fair use was left unresolved.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] In 2016, following a two-week trial, a jury determined that Google's reimplementation of the Java API constituted fair use, but Oracle vowed to appeal the decision.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Oracle won on its appeal, with the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit ruling that Google's use of the APIs did not qualify for fair use.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] In 2019, Google appealed to the Supreme Court of the United States over both the copyrightability and fair use rulings, and the Supreme Court granted review.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the oral hearings in the case were delayed until October 2020.
[src:hardware-abstraction/api] The case was decided by the Supreme Court in Google's favor.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] The **IBM AS/400** (**Application System/400**) is a family of midrange computers from IBM announced in June 1988 and released in August 1988.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] It was the successor to the System/36 and System/38 platforms, and ran the OS/400 operating system.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] Lower-cost but more powerful than its predecessors, an estimated 111,000 installations existed by the end of 1990 and annual revenue reaching $14 billion that year, increasing to 250,000 systems by 1994, and about 500,000 shipped by 1997.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] A key concept in the AS/400 platform is Technology Independent Machine Interface (TIMI), a platform-independent instruction set architecture (ISA) that is translated to native machine language instructions.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] The platform has used this capability to change the underlying processor architecture without breaking application compatibility.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] Early systems were based on a 48-bit CISC instruction set architecture known as the *Internal Microprogrammed Interface* (IMPI), originally developed for the System/38.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] In 1995, the company introduced a new version of the system running on a series of 64-bit PowerPC-derived CPUs, which later were developed into the IBM RS64 family.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] Due to the use of TIMI, applications for the original CISC-based programs continued to run on the new systems without modification, as the TIMI code can be re-translated to the new systems' PowerPC Power ISA native machine code.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] The RS64 was replaced with POWER4 processors in 2001, which was followed by POWER5 and POWER6 in later upgrades.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] The AS/400 went through multiple re-branding exercises, finally becoming the **System i** in 2006.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] In 2008, IBM consolidated the separate System i and System p product lines (which had mostly identical hardware by that point) into a single product line named IBM Power Systems.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] The name "AS/400" is sometimes used informally to refer to the IBM i operating system running on modern Power Systems hardware.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] In the early 1980s, IBM management became concerned that IBM's large number of incompatible midrange computer systems was hurting the company's competitiveness, particularly against Digital Equipment Corporation's VAX.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] A new operating system would be created for Fort Knox, but the operating systems of each platform which Fort Knox was intended to replace would also be ported to the Iliad processor to allow customers to migrate their software to the new platform.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] The Fort Knox project proved to be overly ambitious and ran into multiple delays and changes of scope.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] As the project advanced, the requirement to support IBM 8100 and Series/1 software was dropped.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] When IBM's engineers attempted to port the operating systems and software of their existing platforms, they discovered that it would be impossible without making extensive changes to the Iliad processor for each individual operating system — changes that Iliad's architects were unwilling to make.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] The proposed solution to this was to augment Iliad with operating system-specific co-processors that provided hardware support for a single operating system.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] However, the amount of logic needed in each co-processor grew until the co-processors became the main processor, and the Iliad was relegated to the role of a support processor — thus failing the goal of consolidating on a single processor architecture.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] The Fort Knox project was ultimately cancelled in 1985.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] During the Fort Knox project, a skunkworks project was started at IBM Rochester by engineers who believed that Fort Knox's failure was inevitable.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] These engineers developed code that allowed System/36 applications to run on top of the System/38, and when Fort Knox was cancelled, this skunkworks project evolved into an official project to replace both the System/36 and System/38 with a single new hardware platform.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] The project became known as *Silverlake* (named for Silver Lake in Rochester, Minnesota) and officially began in December 1985.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] The Silverlake hardware was essentially an evolution of the System/38 that reused some of the technology developed for the Fort Knox project.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] Silverlake's goal was to deliver a replacement for the System/36 and System/38 in as short a timeframe as possible, as the Fort Knox project had stalled new product development at Rochester, leaving IBM without a competitive midrange system.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] On its launch in 1986, the System/370-compatible IBM 9370 was positioned as IBM's preferred midrange platform, but failed to achieve the commercial success IBM hoped it would have.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] Much like Silverlake, the 9370 also reused the co-processor developed during the Fort Knox project as its main processor and the same SPD I/O bus that was derived from the Series/1 bus.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] On June 21, 1988, IBM officially announced the Silverlake system as the *Application System/400* (AS/400).
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] The announcement included more than 1,000 software packages written for it by IBM and IBM Business Partners.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] The AS/400 operating system was named *Operating System/400* (OS/400).
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] The creators of the AS/400 originally planned to use the name *System/40*, but IBM had adopted a new product nomenclature around the same time, which led to the Application System/400 name.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] First, IBM began prefixing "System" in product names with words to indicate the intended use or target market of the system (e.g., Personal System/2 and Enterprise System/9000).
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] Second, IBM decided to reserve one- and two-digit model numbers for personal systems (e.g., PS/2 and PS/55), three-digit numbers for midrange systems (e.g., AS/400) and four-digit numbers for mainframes (e.g., ES/9000).
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] The reassignment of two-digit model numbers from midrange systems to personal systems was to prevent the personal systems from running out of single-digit numbers for new products.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] Its RISC technology offered a much better price/performance ratio than AS/400.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] Analysts said that IBM intended to let the proprietary AS/400 and Unix-based RS/6000 compete with each other for midrange customers.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] IBM Rochester reportedly attempted to make RS/6000 less attractive compared to AS/400.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] In 1990, IBM Rochester began work to replace the AS/400's original System/38-derived 48-bit CISC processors with a 96-bit architecture known as *C-RISC* (Commercial RISC).
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] Rather than being a clean-slate design, C-RISC would have added RISC-style and VLIW-style instructions to the AS/400's processor, while maintaining backwards compatibility with the System/370-style *Internal Microprogrammed Interface* (IMPI) instruction set and the microcode used to implement it.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] In 1991, at the request of IBM president Jack Kuehler, a team under the leadership of Frank Soltis delivered a proposal to adapt the 64-bit PowerPC architecture to support the needs of the AS/400 platform.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] Their extensions to the PowerPC architecture, known as *Amazon* (and later as *PowerPC AS*), were approved by IBM management instead of the C-RISC design for development into the next AS/400 processor architecture.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] These extensions include support for tagged memory, as well as assistance for decimal arithmetic.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] IBM initially attempted to create a single PowerPC implementation for both AS/400 and high-end RS/6000 systems known as *Belatrix*.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] The Belatrix project proved to be too ambitious, and was cancelled when it became apparent that it would not deliver on schedule.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] Instead, a pair of AS/400-specific processors were designed at IBM Endicott and IBM Rochester, known as *Cobra* (for low end systems) and *Muskie* (for high end systems) respectively.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] These became the initial implementations of the IBM RS64 processor line.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] The RS64 series continued to be developed as a separate product line at IBM until the POWER4 merged both the RS64 and POWER product lines together.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] Despite the move from IMPI to an entirely different processor architecture, the AS/400's Technology Independent Machine Interface (TIMI) mostly hid the changes from users and applications, and transparently recompiled applications for the new processor architecture.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] The port of OS/400 to the PowerPC AS architecture required a rewrite of most of the code below the TIMI due to the use of IMPI microcode to implement significant quantities of the operating system's low level code.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] This led to the creation of the System Licensed Internal Code (SLIC) - a new implementation of the lower levels of the operating system mostly written in C++.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] The AS/400 family line was rebranded several times in the 1990s and 2000s as IBM introduced newer generations of hardware and operating system.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] In 1994, the *AS/400 Advanced Series* name was used for new models, followed by the rebranding of the product line to *AS/400e* (the *e* standing for e-business) in 1997.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] In 2000, the *eServer iSeries* was introduced as part of its *eServer branding initiative*.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] The eServer iSeries was built on the POWER4 processor from the RS64 processors used by previous generations, meaning that the same processors were used in both the iSeries and pSeries platforms, the latter of which ran AIX.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] In 2004, *eServer i5* (along with OS/400 becoming *i5/OS*) the *5* signifying the use of POWER5 processors, was introduced, replacing the eServer iSeries brand.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] Successive generations of iSeries and pSeries hardware converged until they were essentially the same hardware sold under different names and with different operating systems.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] Some i5 servers were still using the AS/400-specific IBM Machine Type (MT/M 9406–520) and were able to run AIX in a logical partition along i5/OS, while the p5 servers were able to run i5/OS, respectively.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] The licensing for AIX and i5/OS was controlled in the firmware by the POWER hypervisor.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] The final rebranding occurred in 2006, when IBM rebranded the eServer i5 to *System i*.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] In April 2008, IBM introduced the IBM Power Systems line, which was a convergence of System i and System p product lines.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] The first Power Systems machines used the POWER6 processors; i5/OS was renamed as *IBM i* in order to remove the association with POWER5 processors.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] IBM i is sold as one of the operating system options for Power Systems (along with AIX and Linux) instead of being tied to its own hardware platform.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] Although announced in 1988, the AS/400 remains IBM's most recent major architectural shift that was developed wholly internally.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] After the departure of CEO John Akers in 1993, when IBM looked likely to be split up, Bill Gates commented that the only part of IBM that Microsoft would be interested in was the AS/400 division.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] According to Frank Soltis, one of the architects of the AS/400 platform, the AS/400's architecture is defined by five architectural principles.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] Most of these principles are inherited from System/38.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] The high-level instruction set (called TIMI for "Technology Independent Machine Interface" by IBM) allows application programs to take advantage of advances in hardware and software without recompilation.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] TIMI is a virtual instruction set independent of the underlying machine instruction set of the CPU.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] User-mode programs contain both TIMI instructions and the machine instructions of the CPU, thus ensuring hardware independence.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] This is conceptually somewhat similar to the virtual machine architecture of programming environments such as Java and .NET.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] Unlike some other virtual-machine architectures in which the virtual instructions are interpreted at run time, TIMI instructions are never interpreted.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] They constitute an intermediate compile time step and are translated into the processor's instruction set as the final compilation step.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] The TIMI instructions are stored within the final program object, in addition to the executable machine instructions.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] This is how application objects compiled on one processor family (e.g., the original CISC AS/400 48-bit processors) could be moved to a new processor (e.g., PowerPC 64-bit) without re-compilation.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] An application saved from the older 48-bit platform can simply be restored onto the new 64-bit platform where the operating system discards the old machine instructions and re-translates the TIMI instructions into 64-bit instructions for the new processor.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] The system's instruction set defines all pointers as 128-bit.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] This was the original design feature of the System/38 (S/38) in the mid-1970s planning for future use of faster processors, memory, and an expanded address space.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] The original AS/400 CISC models used the same 48-bit address space as the S/38.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] The address space was expanded in 1995 when the RISC PowerPC RS64 64-bit CPU processor replaced the 48-bit CISC processor.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] OS/400 (now known as IBM i) is the native operating system of the AS/400 platform and was the sole operating system supported on the original AS/400 hardware.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] Many of the advanced features associated with the AS/400 are implemented in the operating system as opposed to the underlying hardware, which changed significantly throughout the life of the AS/400 platform.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] Features include a RDBMS (Db2 for i), a menu-driven interface, support for multiple users, block-oriented terminal support (IBM 5250), and printers.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] Unlike the "everything is a file" principle of Unix and its derivatives, on IBM i everything is an object (with built-in persistence and garbage collection).
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] IBM uses a single-level store virtual memory architecture in the AS/400 platform.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] For 64-bit PowerPC processors, the virtual address resides in the rightmost 64 bits of a pointer while it was 48 bits in the S/38 and CISC AS/400.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] The 64-bit address space references main memory and disk as a single address set, which is the single-level store concept.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] Later generations of hardware are also capable of supporting various guest operating systems, including SSP, AIX, Linux, Microsoft Windows 2000, and Windows Server 2003.
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] While OS/400, AIX, and Linux are supported on the POWER processors on LPARs (logical partitions), Windows is supported with either single-processor internal blade servers (IXS) or externally linked multiple-processor servers (IXA and iSCSI).
[src:hardware-abstraction/as-400] SSP guests were supported using emulation from OS/400 V3R6 through V4R4 using the Advanced 36 Machine facility of the operating system, a feature distinct from the System/36 Environment compatibility layer, which requires System/36 software to be recompiled.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] A **hardware abstraction** is software that provides access to hardware in a way that hides details that might otherwise make using the hardware difficult.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] Typically, access is provided via a software interface that allows devices that share a level of similarity to be accessed via the same software actions even though the devices provide different hardware interfaces.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] A hardware abstraction can support the development of cross-platform applications.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] Early software was developed without a hardware abstraction, which required a developer to understand multiple devices in order to provide compatibility.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] With hardware abstraction, the software leverages the abstraction to access significantly different hardware via the same interface.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] The abstraction (often implemented in the operating system) then performs the hardware-specific operations.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] This allows software to be compatible with all devices supported by the abstraction.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] Consider a joystick device, of which there are many physical implementations.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] It could be accessible via an application programming interface (API) that supports common operations such as moving, firing, configuring sensitivity, and so on across variety of different joysticks.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] A Joystick abstraction hides details (e.g., register format, I2C address) so programmers using the abstraction do not need to understand details regarding the device's physical interface.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] This also allows code reuse since the same code can process standardized messages from any kind of implementation which supplies the joystick abstraction.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] For example, a "nudge forward" can be from a potentiometer or from a capacitive touch sensor that recognizes "swipe" gestures, as long as they both provide a signal related to "movement".
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] As physical limitations may vary with hardware, an API can do little to hide that, other than by assuming a "least common denominator" model.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] Thus, certain deep architectural decisions from the implementation may become relevant to users of a particular instantiation of an abstraction.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] A good metaphor is the abstraction of transportation.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] Both bicycling and driving a car are transportation.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] They both have commonalities (e.g., it must be steered) and physical differences (e.g., power source).
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] One can always specify the abstraction "drive to" and let the implementer decide whether bicycling or driving a car is best.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] The "wheeled terrestrial transport" function is abstracted and the details of "how to drive" are encapsulated.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] A high-level programming language provides for hardware abstraction by allowing a programmer write an algorithm without using instructions that are unique to a central processing unit (CPU) or its instruction set architecture (ISA) – the primitive operations of a CPU.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] For example, a compiler generates the CPU-specific instructions for a particular ISA.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] In this way, source code can support portability across multiple platforms.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] A **hardware abstraction layer** (HAL) is an abstraction layer, implemented in software, between the physical hardware of a computer and the software that runs on that computer.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] Its function is to hide differences in hardware from most of the operating system kernel, so that most of the kernel-mode code does not need to be changed to run on systems with different hardware.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] On Microsoft Windows, HAL can basically be considered to be the driver for the motherboard and allows instructions from higher level computer languages to communicate with lower level components, but prevents direct access to the hardware.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] CP/M (CP/M BIOS), DOS (DOS BIOS), Solaris, Linux, BSD, macOS, and some other portable operating systems also have a HAL, even if it is not explicitly designated as such.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] Some operating systems, such as Linux, have the ability to insert one while running, like Adeos.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] The NetBSD operating system is widely known as having a clean hardware abstraction layer which allows it to be highly portable.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] As part of this system are `uvm(9)`/`pmap(9)`, `bus_space(9)`, `bus_dma(9)`, and other subsystems.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] Popular buses which are used on more than one architecture are also abstracted, such as ISA, EISA, PCI, PCIe, etc., allowing drivers to also be highly portable with a minimum of code modification.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] Operating systems having a defined HAL are more easily portable across different hardware.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] This is especially important for embedded systems that run on dozens of different platforms.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] In a software stack, the HAL resides below the application programming interface (API), whereas the application layer (often written in a high-level language) resides above the API and communicates with the hardware by calling functions in the API.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] The Windows NT kernel has a HAL in the kernel space between hardware and the executive services that are contained in the file `ntoskrnl.exe` under `hal.dll`.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] For example, the SGI Intel x86-based workstations were not IBM PC compatible workstations, but due to the HAL, Windows 2000 ran on them.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] Since Windows Vista and Windows Server 2008, the HAL used is automatically determined during startup; in fact since Windows Vista, Windows NT only allows ACPI based HAL.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] The Windows CE also has a HAL called **OEM Adaptation Layer** (OAL), and it's compiled to `oal.exe` or `oal.dll`, and it's included in the `nk.bin` boot image.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] In Windows 9x, both the actual kernel and the actual HAL is `vmm32.vxd`.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] An "extreme" example of a HAL can be found in the System/38 and AS/400 architectures, currently implemented in the IBM i operating system.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] Most compilers for those systems generate an abstract machine code; the Licensed Internal Code, or LIC, translates this virtual machine code into native code for the processor on which it is running and executes the resulting native code.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] Android introduced a HAL known as the "vendor interface" (codenamed "Project Treble") on version 8.0 "Oreo".
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] It abstracts low-level code from the Android OS framework, and they must be made forward compatible to support future versions of Android to ease the development of firmware updates.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] Before Project Treble, Android relied on various non-standardized legacy HALs.
[src:hardware-abstraction/hardware-abstraction] Halium is an Android-based HAL used by several mobile operating systems such as Ubuntu Touch and LuneOS to run on smartphones with Android pre-installed.
